<HEADLINE> Sudan to Restore Expropriated Egyptian Property </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- In a step towards improving the
long-hit ties with Egypt, Sudanese President Omar al-Bashir has
ordered necessary arrangements to restore Egyptian property in
Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"The arrangements fit within the Khartoum government's policies
to remove obstacles impeding progress of the long-established ties
with Cairo," said a statement released by the Sudanese Embassy
here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to sources of the embassy, al-Bashir's instructions
cover the branch of Cairo University in Khartoum, public schools
and the guesthouse of an Egyptian irrigation and hydrological
survey team.
</P>
<P>
These properties have been seized by Khartoum over chilling
relations after an Islamist-backed government assumed power in
Sudan in 1989.
</P>
<P>
Ad hoc committees composed of officials of the Sudanese
irrigation and education ministries began as of Sunday putting
al-Bashir's directives into effect, said the sources.
</P>
<P>
Al-Bashir's decision came just a month after the two countries
resumed the river Nile navigation after a hiatus of three years, a
move hailed by both sides as a good turn after a long period of
deteriorating ties.
</P>
<P>
The neighbors were at odds over a border dispute and have
traded accusations of harboring militants and oppositions, but
there are signs of a tentative thaw in relations.
</P>
<P>
A top-level Egyptian delegation, headed by Prime Minister Kamal
el-Ganzouri, recently went to Khartoum to convey condolences over
the death of Sudanese First Vice President al-Zubeir Mohammed Salih
in a plane accident.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa Saturday voiced pleasure
over the amelioration in relations between the two neighbors,
saying he would hold talks with his Sudanese counterpart Mustafa
Ismail in Cairo on March 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
