<HEADLINE> Israel Strives to Thwart Cook's Har Homa Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli government is making
intense efforts Sunday to thwart a planned visit by British
Foreign Secretary Robin Cook to the controversial site Har Homa
in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
At the weekly Israeli Cabinet session, Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu described as "unacceptable" Cook's planned visit to Har
Homa with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Minister of
Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Ministry has been ordered to hold intense contacts
with British Foreign Office in a bid to cancel Cook's visit to Har
Homa, where Israel is building a Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is holding the rotating presidency of
European Union, is due here on Tuesday as part of his upcoming
Middle Eastern tour that also includes Palestine, Egypt, Jordan,
Lebanon and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Israel began the construction of Har Homa settlement in March
last year, precipitating the deadlock in Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks. The PNA charged Israel for violating the Oslo accords which
demand both sides refrain from changing the status quo of
Jerusalem, whose fate should be settled through permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Husseini was vague about the exact itinerary of Cook's Har
Homa tour and his role in it. Local English daily The Jerusalem
Post quoted him as saying Sunday that he and Cook would hold a
meeting, but he was not clear about the exact plan for the Har
Homa visit. "If he (Cook) asks me to go there I will go with him,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government was also upset by the reports that Cook
would launch a new initiative to break the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian talks by demanding Israel carry out 15-20
percent further pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The government, which is only willing to redeploy troops from 9
percent of West Bank in the second redeployment, has said it would
not compromise on any issues over its security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
