<HEADLINE> Vietnam Plans to Increase Export of Tea in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to export 35,000
tonnes of dried tea buds in 1998, a 12 percent year-on-year
increase, according to Vietnam's Ministry of Agriculture and
Rural Development.
</P>
<P>
The export in the first two months of this year amounted to
nearly 5,000 tonnes, a 53.5 percent growth as compared
to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
To encourage tea planting, Vietnam's Tea Corporation has raised
its price for the purchase of fresh tea buds by 10 percent as
compared to last year.
</P>
<P>
This year, the corporation will concentrate efforts in
fertilizing land and promoting intensive farming on the present tea
acreage of 70,000 hectares which are expected to yield 10 tonnes
of fresh bud per hectare. Meanwhile another 5,000 hectares will
be planted with a new tea strain which can yield 15 tonnes of buds
per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The corporation also plans to put six new processing factories,
equipped with modern technology, into operation this year, and
build a number of small-sized factories in tea growing areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
