<HEADLINE> Zimbabwen Ruling Party Supporters Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- A number of the Zimbabwean ruling
ZANU (pf) supporters Sunday agreed that the constitution must be
amended to ensure a limited presidential term, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was made when the 200 ZANU supporters met in
Bulawayo, the second biggest city in the country. They were
addressed by Home Affairs Minister Dumiso Dabengwa who said that
the request for a limited presidential term did not mean that
they wanted president robert mugabe to go.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe has been leader of the country since independence in
1980.
</P>
<P>
Dabengwa, a member of the ruling party politburo said, ''In
all this debate, nobody is saying the current leadership should
go.''
</P>
<P>
He said that people should be allowed to debate the question
of succession in the leadership of both the party and government.
</P>
<P>
''Some of us in leadership are now old. They are in the
twilight of their lives. They will need to be replaced,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
''It is you who should choose the next leadership. A
leadership that will decentralise power. A leadership that has
national appeal and will treat all Zimbabweans equally,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
On the constitution, Dabengwa said, ''The main issue being
debated on the national constitution is the term of the
president. Some people say the constitution must specify that a
president should serve two five-year terms only, while others say
that part of the constitution should be left as it is.''
</P>
<P>
''These are the things we are appealing to you to discuss
seriously and make recommendations through the party hierarchy
and subsequently to parliament until the issue is resolved,'' the
minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
