<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Faces Shortage of Vaccines for Livestock </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe is facing serious
shortages of vaccines to combat livestock diseases because its
major South African supplier is failing to meet the demand, a
senior government official said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Veterinary Services Director Stuart Hargreaves told the
Zimbabwe News Agency that Onderstepoort, South Africa's largest
veterinary institute, could not produce enough vaccines due to
staff shortages.
</P>
<P>
South African press recently reported that five out of the six
of the institute's vaccine specialists were leaving the country
for greener pastures.
</P>
<P>
"We are very concerned about the shortage because a disaster
is imminent if an outbreak of major diseases occurs," the
director said.
</P>
<P>
Vaccines for combating endemic diseases such as heart water
and gall sickness had already run out of stock in Zimbabwe, he
said.
</P>
<P>
The country was not experiencing any major animal disease
outbreaks, save for a few cattle dying from tick-borne diseases,
Hargreaves noted.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is relatively quiet these day," Hargreaves
said, "but we are on the watch for any serious outbreaks."
</P>
<P>
Veterinary experts in Namibia had been warned against an
expected outbreak of lumpy skin diseases, another sickness for
which vaccine stocks at Onderstepoort were critically low.
</P>
<P>
Vaccines for foot-and-mouth and lung disease were also said to
be running out fast. 
</P>
</TEXT>
