<HEADLINE> IGAD Summit to Open in Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Prime Minister
Meles Zenawi Sunday left here for Djibouti to attend the
Inter-Governmental Authority on Development (IGAD) summit due to
open on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers of the IGAD member states have begun their
meeting there Saturday for preparation of the forthcoming summit.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believed that the Somali conflict and southern
Sudan civil war will be on the agenda of the summit.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached by Somali two main faction
leaders Hussein Aideed and Ali Mahdi, at the end of last year, a
national reconciliation conference would have been held at Baidoa
in February this year. However, the Baidoa conference failed to
be held as schedule. Hostilities and fightings still prevail in
Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The 67th ordinary session of the Council of Ministers of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) held at the end of February
pointed out: ''The peace and national reconciliation process is
at a critical stage''in Somalia and urged ''all the parties to
work together with a view to achieving national reconciliation''.
</P>
<P>
The seven member states of IGAD are Eritrea, Ethiopia, Kenya,
Uganda, Sudan, Djibouti and Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
