<HEADLINE> Retail Trading in Bonds to Be Conducted on Lusaka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Zambia announced on
Sunday that all retail trading in bonds will be conducted on the
Lusaka Stock Exchange (LUSE) with effect from Monday.
</P>
<P>
This will promote transparency in market dealings and improve
market efficiency while reducing the risks associated with using
papers as well as the continual cost of safe custody, Zambia News
Agency (ZANA) quoted Kabinga Pan de, the public relations manager
of the central bank, as saying.
</P>
<P>
He explained that this action to activate secondary market
liquidity and improve price formation requires the broadest
possible participation, in particular the engagement of small
investors.
</P>
<P>
The minimum value of orders placed on the LUSE for trading
will be 100,000 Zambian Kwacha (about 65 U.S. Dollars) to
encourage more participants.
</P>
<P>
These measures, said Pande, will enhance liquidity in the
Zambian financial system and result in better price formation in
addition to laying a foundation for the development of longer
dated capital market instruments by the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The central bank official urged the public and other non-bank
institutions interested in investing in bonds to contact
commercial banks, the only institutions to conduct all retail
trading and rediscounting of bonds on the LUSE. 
</P>
</TEXT>
