<HEADLINE> Health Service Coverage Rises in Ethiopian Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Health Bureau of Afar
Region announced on Sunday that the health service coverage in
the region which was rather low four years back, has now risen to
11 percent.
</P>
<P>
Afar Region which located in north-eastern part of Ethiopia is
a backward region in the country. The rise in health service
coverage should be attributed to a rapid increase in the number
of health professionals and institutions in the region over the
last four years.
</P>
<P>
According to the bureau of the Afar Region, the number of
health stations and clinics in the region which was only two and
15 respectively in 1994, now reached four and 47 respectively.
Two new hospitals have also been built in the region during the
stated period. At present there are more than 350 health
professionals in the region.
</P>
<P>
The region plans to increase the health coverage to 29 percent
in the near future with particular emphasis to be put on
expanding services to the rural parts of the region.
</P>
<P>
The health service coverage in Ethiopia currently stands at 40
percent and the nation is determined to increase it to 50
percent in the coming five years, said an announcement
made recently by the Ministry of Health. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
