<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Thriving East African Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Zhang Dacheng)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 15 (Xinhua) - Though only two-year-old on
Saturday, the East African Cooperation (EAC) has laid a solid
foundation for common development and prosperity for its three
member states, Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Stretching roots back to the former East African Community
which collapsed in 1977, the EAC has rekindled hope for a total
of some 80 million Kiswahili-speaking residents along the Great
Rift Valley, which is well known as one of the cradles of the
human civilization.
</P>
<P>
The defunct community, founded in accordance with a treaty
signed by presidents of the three neighbouring countries in
Kampala, Uganda, in June 1967, several years after their
independence from the western colonizers, explored positively
regional cooperation by establishing joint ventures in the
sectors of railway, ports, telecommunication, aviation as well as
banks.
</P>
<P>
However, the 10n-year-old Community disintegrated in February
1977 following the development of independent railway, aviation
and other companies in its member states.
</P>
<P>
Spurred by waves of the worldwide regional cooperation,
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda united again on November 22, 1991 by
forming a Permanent Tripartite Commission at the ministerial
level, and finally, the East African Cooperation was ushered in
on March 14, 1996.
</P>
<P>
The new EAC, whose Secretariat is based in Tanzania's northern
city of Arusha, the so-called "heart of the three states", is
entrusted with a mandate to promote a people-centered economic,
political, social and cultural development on the basis of
balance, equity and mutual benefit by exploiting the natural and
human resources in the region.
</P>
<P>
From the very beginning, the EAC identified economic
cooperation as its key priority and its immediate focus was put
on economic infrastructure in the sectors of transport,
telecommunication, energy as well as movement of capital,
information and technologies.
</P>
<P>
Great progress have been made over the past two years. For
example, the currencies of the three states were made
convertible, the double taxation lifted and the oil pipeline from
Eldoret, Kenya, to Kampala of Uganda extended.
</P>
<P>
The most important achievement is that a mutual-confidence has
been built among the three EAC states which have mapped out a
series of macro-economic growth plans with the EAC Development
Strategy (1997-2000) at the core. The plans have won extensive
support from international and regional organs such as the World
Bank, the International Monetary Fund, the Organization of
African Unity, the Southern Africa Development Community and from
countries in Europe, Asia and America.
</P>
<P>
"Indeed, a lot still remains to be done but all indications
are that we are moving on the right track," said Francis
Muthaura, the EAC Executive Secretary, in a statement released
Saturday to mark the second anniversary of the EAC's foundation.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by the increasing interest shown by both local and
foreign investors, he said, the EAC will hold a two-day donors'
meeting by the end of this May to collect fund for the ambitious
regional road and railway networks.
</P>
<P>
An EAC summit is also planned in June to sign an agreement to
upgrade the cooperation to the treaty level and to formally
launch the long-expected east African passports to guarantee free
movement of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
Not long ago, sources from the Tanzanian Defense Ministry
disclosed that Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda will take a joint
military exercise in northern Tanzania in the near future, which
will be the first of its kind in the history.
</P>
<P>
At a cocktail party in Arusha on Saturday evening, Jakaya
Kikwete, the Tanzanian Minister of Foreign Affairs and
International Cooperation, and current Chairman of the EAC
Permanent Tripartite Commission, outlined EAC's long-range
perspective as a single market and an East African Federation.
</P>
<P>
Julius Nyerere, Tanzania's first president since independence,
once said that one of the important reasons for the slow African
economic development is that many African countries whose borders
were demarcated maliciously by the western colonizers, are too
small to engage in large-scale economic construction.
</P>
<P>
The 76-year-old Nyerere, who is respectfully called "Muwalim"
( means "teacher" in the Kiswahili language), said last month
that he has been longing for an early unity of all the African
countries, especially the three in east Africa.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that I would be the first permanent representative of
the `East African Federation' to the United Nations," said the
Muwalim, voicing the aspirations of the people of the three EAC
members for a common development and prosperity.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
