<HEADLINE> Arab Ministers to Sign Anti-Terrorism Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Arab ministers of justice and
interior will sign in April the first collective Arab
anti-terrorism and extremism pact after four years of debate, the
Middle East News Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will convene at the Arab League headquarters in
Cairo on April 22 to endorse the final draft of the deal ahead of
the signing ceremony, said the Egyptian Minister of Justice Farouq
Seif el-Nasr, who unveiled the date of the signing.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting of an ad hoc technical committee, which
convened here last week, a consensus was reached on the final
draft of the pact after a thorough revision.
</P>
<P>
"The deal is designed to enhance inter-Arab cooperation in the
face of terrorism and extremism threatening the Arab region,"
el-Nasr said.
</P>
<P>
The deal underlined principles of Islam, international law, the
Charter of the United Nations and related anti-terrorism
international agreements, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The draft agreement gives peoples the right to struggle against
foreign occupation to win independence and maintain
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
Extradition of criminals, joint anti-terrorism research and an
identification of terrorism are included in the draft blueprint.
</P>
</TEXT>
