<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Cuts Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Uganda has cut its budget by 14
billion Ugandan Shillings (some 13 million U.S. Dollars) this
month to fit its revenue collection condition, the Monitor
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to an estimate made by Keith Muhakanizi, the special
adviser to the finance minister, the country failed to realize
its revenue target by 22 billion Shillings, and has to spend an
extra expenditure of 6 billion Shillings due to El-Nino on
repairing roads, treating cholera patients.
</P>
<P>
Uganda decided to cut a large proportion of its non-wage
expenditure in government agencies and cancel all development
expenditure for this month.
</P>
<P>
The cut will reduce consumption and most likely slow down
economic growth for this financial year, local analysts noted.
</P>
<P>
The government made the decision to qualify for a proposed 700
million debt relief in April under World Bank and International
Monetary Fund program, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Imports form Kenya could not reach Uganda in time and
quantities due to destruction of the roads and railway from
Mombasa (Kenya port city) )to Kampala, and that has a negative
influence on revenue collection, said Lawrence Kiiza, the
Commissioner for Taxation in the Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Import contributes 60 percent of the total revenue of the
country, Kiiza said.
</P>
<P>
Farmers can not transport their products to market in time and
this greatly reduced the income of the people in countryside.
</P>
<P>
Majority of the rural population could not earn their usual
money and they could not buy things produced in cities and towns,
that also means the government could not get taxes as usual, he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
