<HEADLINE> Israeli Key Minister Submits Pullback Plan from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli National Infrastructure
Minister Ariel Sharon submitted a proposal about Israeli troop
pullback from southern Lebanon to a cabinet meeting on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the proposal, which Sharon made public in an
interview with a television station on Friday, Israel would
conduct a unilateral, gradual and phased troop pullback from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Israel would issue a warning that any attacks
launched on Israel from Lebanese soil after Israeli troop pullout
would be met with severe retaliation.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared to implement a pullout in stages while
monitoring any results that might ensue," he said, adding that
"Israel would make it clear in advance that it would hold Lebanon
responsible for any future cross-border attacks."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Affairs and Defense Committee of the Israeli
Knesset (parliament) will examine all proposals on Monday
concerning troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's proposal has won the support of prominent Knesset
member of the opposition Labor party Yossi Beilin, who is a
fervent advocate of Israeli withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Sharon's plan is a positive move which would lead to eventual
pullout of the Israeli Defense Force from Lebanon, Beilin told
Israel Radio on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has offered to withdraw from southern Lebanon under the
United Nations Security Council Resolution 425 if the Lebanon
agrees to curb guerrilla attacks on Israel from its territory.
</P>
<P>
But Lebanon has rejected the offer, maintaining that the U.N.
resolution, which was passed in 1978, demands an unconditional
withdrawal by the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a security zone in 1985 in southern Lebanon to
allegedly protect its northern areas from cross-border attacks by
Lebanese Muslim guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
It has been waging a war of attrition with Lebanese resistance
forces, in which hundreds of its soldiers have lost lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
