<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania to Honor Debt Repayment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian President
Benjamin Mkapa has assured creditors that Tanzania will continue
to honor its internal and external debt.
</P>
<P>
In a speech broadcast Sunday night to the whole nation, the
president said he feels obliged to correct recent misleading
media reports that the country will halt repayment of debt after
a severe flood that has brought economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
"There is an urgent need to allay fears of the internal and
external creditors," Mkapa said through Radio Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"We need to acquire more loans since our economy is still not
self-reliant," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Explaining how the country's economy is still dependent on
foreign loans, Mkapa said out of the 1997/1998 annual budget of
975.6 billion Shillings (about 1.45 billion US Dollars), 340
billion Shillings are expected to be raised from foreign loans
and grants.
</P>
<P>
In addition, by the year 2000 Tanzania will require an
estimated sum of 8.4 billion US Dollars in the form of loans and
grants to finance the country's development and expenditure.
</P>
<P>
"In the face of such an extent of dependency, where do we get
the audacity to refuse to repay our debts?" he asked.
</P>
<P>
He said the only audacity Tanzanians could show is to develop
the economy through austerity measures and speed up economic
growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's external debt has reached 7.9 billion US Dollars,
more than 10 times the country's export earnings per year, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, even if we were to spend our entire export
earnings without importing anything, as little as a single drop
of petrol and an aspirin tablet, it will take us 10 years to
finish repaying our external debt," the president observed.
</P>
<P>
Despite the heavy debt burden, the president said the
Tanzanian government has decided to accelerate debt repayment
pace so as to maintain honesty and dignity of the nation.
</P>
<P>
The loans, he pointed out, have in fact helped Tanzania a lot
in building infrastructures, providing social services and
launching industrial projects.
</P>
<P>
"The main task facing us is to initiate sound economic
policies, maintain good relations with donors and creditors,
enhance the spirit of self-reliance, so as to sustain the
country's economic development tempo," Mkapa said.
</P>
<P>
However, he believed that it is necessary to create a
conducive atmosphere for negotiations on the possibility of
reducing repayment burden with creditors, which have produced
positive results, such as debt relief and extension of grace
periods of repayment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
