<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Prepares for Conflict Prevention Mechanism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Minister of the 16-member Economic
Community of West African States (ECOWAS) have worked out
guidelines for the establishment of a sub-regional mechanism for
conflict prevention, management and resolution as well as
peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
The move was made at the just-concluded two-day meeting of the
ECOWAS foreign ministers in Yamoussoukro, Cote d'Ivoire, the News
Agency of Nigeria reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The official agency quoted Nigerian Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi
as saying that details of the mechanism would be worked out by
experts and technical staff in liaison with the ECOWAS
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, preceded by that of ministers of defense and
internal affairs, was in response to the mandate of the ECOWAS
heads of state at their fourth extraordinary meeting in Togo last
December to implement such protocols so as to strengthen
sub-regional security and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The protocols relate to conflict prevention, early warning,
cross-border crime control and proliferation of and traffic in
small arms and narcotics.
</P>
<P>
Ikimi, who is also chairman of the ECOWAS Council of Foreign
Ministers, said the mechanism had the prospect of being
replicated by other sub-regional groups on the continent.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held after the overthrow of Sierra Leone's
military junta by ECOWAS peacekeeping force (ECOMOG) and the
reinstatement of ousted President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, reviewed
efforts to establish a sub-regional framework for security and
stability.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also reviewed and assessed the security
situation in the sub-region, particularly in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that the Nigerian-led ECOMOG is expected to play
a key role in the proposed mechanism.  
</P>
</TEXT>
