<HEADLINE> Greece Announces Measures for Restructuring Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government Sunday
announced a package of drastic measures for restructuring its
ailing economy and fiscal adjustment after drachma's entry into
the European exchange rate mechanism (ERM) as of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the measures, Greek National Economy and Finance
Minister Yannos Papantoniou stressed that all such measures would
be implemented within the next 18 months.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the Greek national currency's new parity to the
European currency unit (ecu) was set at 357.00 drachmas against
one ecu, denoting a 14 percent devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Athens asked to join the ERM, saying that this would lead the
country's economy to strong "self-fueling" development.
</P>
<P>
The package reportedly provides for the partial privatization
of 11 public companies and three or four state-run banks in 1998
and 1999, with the state retaining minimum 51 percent stakes.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government will also streamline other loss-making
enterprises including Olympic airways, railways, urban transport
and the post-office in accordance with the measures.
</P>
<P>
Papantoniou stressed that the fiscal adjustment measures aimed
at reducing public deficits to 2.4 percent and 2.1 percent of the
gross domestic production (GDP) in 1998 and 1999, as well as bring
down inflation to 2.5 percent by the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
