<HEADLINE> Israel's General Killed in Chopper Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 15 (Xinhua) -- An Israeli Air Force (IAF)
brigadier general and his crewman were killed Sunday morning when
their Cobra attack helicopter crashed into the Mediterranean Sea,
Israel TV channel 1 said.
</P>
<P>
Brig. Gen. Tal Shmuel Eldar, 45, and 20-year-old second
lieutenant Ilan Gur were killed in the chopper crash. Eldar was
the highest-ranking IAF officer ever killed in an military air
accident.
</P>
<P>
The crash occurred about 24 kilometers north of Tel Aviv, off
Kibbutz Gash and the chopper was headed for Palmachim air force
base, about 16 kilometers south of Tel Aviv, where Eldar was
commander, the TV added.
</P>
<P>
The pilot of another military helicopter flying escort
alongside said he initially saw the chopper's tail shaking. Then
it swerved hard, lost speed and fell apart.
</P>
<P>
The chopper disintegrated in midair, with the tail breaking
off and hitting the propeller before the wreckage plummeted into
the sea, the pilot added.
</P>
<P>
This was the second IAF incident in March. On March 2, an IAF
F-15D jet fighter flying low over the West Bank in a routine
training crashed into a mountain near Nablus, killing two officer
on board.
</P>
<P>
Israeli navy boats and helicopters have ferreted about in the
area following the crash in the morning, but the bodies had not
been recovered.
</P>
<P>
The army has opened an investigation of the crash and grounded
its Cobra fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
