<HEADLINE> 54,000 lepers Treated in Nigeria in 10 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- More tha 54,000 cases of leprosy
have been treated in Nigeria in the past decade, the News Agency
of Nigeria reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, when the national tuberculosis and
leprosy control program began in 1988, Nigeria had about 200,000
reported cases of leprosy.
</P>
<P>
The people affected with the ailment were treated free through
"multi-drug therapy" approach with drugs suppled by the sasakawa
Foundation through the World Health Organization, said Chukwu
Ekezie of the program.
</P>
<P>
He stated that 20 percent of those who had been treated and
discharged were now undergoing rehabilitation in lepers colonies
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
However, due to the poor state of facilities in the colonies
and the beliefs that the disease makes the patient an outcast,
among other factors, lepers are seen begging on a Lagos
expressway.
</P>
<P>
A local foundation is now planning to evacuate the lepers
begging to their colony in Edo State more than 200 km to the
east.  
</P>
</TEXT>
