<HEADLINE> Trips to Athens, London Fruitful: Cyprus President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides said on Sunday that his week-long trip to Greece and
Britain have been fruitful.
</P>
<P>
"The objectives of my trip were fully accomplished, since our
proposal to the Turkish Cypriots to join the government's
negotiating team was favorably accepted (by European Union
members)," Clerides told reporters upon his return from London,
where he attended the European Conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference participated by the leaders of the 15 EU members
and 11 central and eastern European countries was aimed at
discussing issues concerning EU's enlargement process.
</P>
<P>
"I am satisfied with the fact that all countries (of the EU)
have appreciated our gesture, describing it ... as courageous and
imaginative, giving the opportunity to the Turkish Cypriot side to
respond positively," Clerides added.
</P>
<P>
But he expressed regret that Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash has rejected the proposal - Denktash described the offer
for Turkish Cypriots to join the accession talks as a "Byzantine
intrigue and a trap."
</P>
<P>
Prior to his London trip, Clerides paid a three-day visit to
Athens and discussed the offer with Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis.
</P>
<P>
EU foreign ministers agreed at a meeting in Edinburgh, Britain,
on Saturday to open accession talks with Cyprus on March 31, as
scheduled, with or without Turkish Cypriots' participation.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third of the Mediterranean island after a failed
coup by Greek Cypriot supporters for a union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared unilaterally in 1983 a breakaway
"Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus," which was only recognized
by Turkey, against the internationally recognized Republic of
Cyprus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
