<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leftwing Parties Confirm Grasp of France in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- France's leftwing parties Sunday
confirmed their grasp of France in the regional council elections
by winning 37 percent of the votes, against 28.5 percent by the
rightwing oppositions and 15.7 percent by the far-right National
Front.
</P>
<P>
This is the second defeat in a row for the Gaullist Rally for
the Republic (RPR) and its central-right ally of Union for French
Democracy (UDF), since the early legislative elections held in May
and June 1997.
</P>
<P>
The latest account jointly issued by the CSA polling
institution, France 3 television and Radio France said that the
Socialists, Communists, ecologists and other smaller leftwing
parties have won 37 percent of the votes, while the RPR and UDF
obtained 28.5 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
The National Front won 15.7 percent of the votes and other
rightwing parties won 6.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear so far who has won the majority of the
municiple parliament of Paris region, or Ile-de-France, but the
leftist parties won a narrow majority in the traditional rightwing
stronghold of Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur with 40 to 42 seats,
against 38 to 40 seats by RPR and UDF.
</P>
<P>
The PRP and UDF maintained their majority in the local
parliaments of Alsace, Lorraine, Basse-Normandie, the Pays de
Loire and Rhone Alpes, while the leftwing parties won majority
seats in Aquitaine, Languedoc-Roussillon, Limousin, Picardie,
Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Midi-Pyrenees, Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur.
</P>
<P>
After the primary results came out, the First Secretary of the
Socialist Party Francois Hollande said: "This evening, the result
is attained."
</P>
<P>
The RPR-UDF candidate for the presidency of the Paris council,
former Prime Minister Edouard Balladur, said that the opposition
"carry collectively the responsibility" for the new defeat.
</P>
<P>
He urged all the "Republican and liberal rightwing" parties
to create a new organization to renew the RPR and UDF.
</P>
<P>
The president of the far-right National Front Jean-Marie Le Pen
said that his party has become "the only national opposition
force" after the election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
