<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia, Angola to Discuss Border Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambia and Angola are to hold a
joint meeting soon to discuss the situation along their common
border, Zambian Foreign Minister Keli Walubita said here on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, military inspections on the common border will be
carried out by both countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the statement as a reaction to Angola's
allegation that Zambian territory has been used to ferry arms to
Angola's former rebel movement the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Walubita said that the alleged supply of arms to UNITA through
Zambia has already been referred to the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and that Zambia is working with Angola to minimize
the tension between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Angolan Ambassador to Zambia Manuel Augusto
told a news briefing here that some Zambians have been supplying
weapons to the UNITA and that the Zambian territory is used in
many ways by these Zambians who support UNITA.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador described the situation in Zambian-Angolan
border as " serious", saying the border is almost under UNITA's
control.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Angola will try in its own ways to ensure that
Zambian territory is not used by the UNITA.
</P>
<P>
But Zambian President Frederick Chiluba last Thursday denied
that his government has any involvement in the supply of arms to
any country.
</P>
<P>
"We are a very peaceful and friendly nation and we have no
capacity to give arms to UNITA," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
After Angola's independence in 1976, the UNITA fought a civil
war for about 20 years against the government. Although the two
sides signed the Lusaka Peace Accord in 1994, peace has not
prevailed all over the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
