<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Parliament Adjourns until March 28 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Kuwaiti National Assembly
(Parliament) decided on Monday to adjourn its current session
until March 28 due to the resignation of the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Because of its resignation, the government would not be
represented in the current or upcoming parliamentary sessions,
Parliament Speaker Ahmed Abdul Aziz Al-Sadoun said.
</P>
<P>
This has forced the parliament to take the decision, he added.
</P>
<P>
Under the Kuwaiti constitution, the 50-member parliament can
not hold sessions without government representation.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti cabinet resigned on Sunday after parliament members
intended to press ahead with a no-confidence motion against
Information Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah over display of
controversial books at the Arab Book Fair last month.
</P>
<P>
The move has been seen as an effort of the government to show
solidarity with the minister so as to abort parliament's
no-confidence motion attempt.
</P>
<P>
Kuwaiti Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah has re-named Crown
Prince Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah as Prime Minister
and asked him to form a new cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
