<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Exports 105 Tonnes of Caviar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Iran exported 105 tonnes of caviar
worth about 11 million U.S. dollars during the current Iranian
fiscal year which ends March 20, the official news agency IRNA
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Fisheries Commercial Company Mohammad
Reza Hosseini told local press Sunday that the export of caviar
registered a 5 percent growth compared with the previous year.
</P>
<P>
He did not give the total amount of caviar harvested during the
year, but said the country expected to export 130-140 tonnes in
the next Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
Caviar is made of roe of the Caspian Sea sturgeon and called
"black gold" for its preciousness. Iran is a main caviar exporter
in the Caspian region, followed by Russia.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to preserve the delicious resource of the Caspian,
Hosseini said, Iran reduced the catching of sturgeon from 3,200
tonnes 10 years ago to 1,500 tonnes in the current Iranian year.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that sturgeon in the Caspian was in great
jerpardy due to increasing illegal fishing and water pollution.
With the start of exploration for oil and gas in the world's
largest lake, some experts warned, the fish is faced with possible
extinction.
</P>
<P>
Hosseini said that the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES) in its
conference held in Zimbabwe last June decided that caviar trade
should be covered as endangered plants and animals.
</P>
<P>
Iran joined CITES in 1972, which currently has 135 members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
