<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Launches Joint Venture with NEC for Integrated Circuit Design </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A Sino-Japanese joint venture for
integrated circuit design was established here today as part of
Project 909, the largest in China's electronics industry.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract signed today, the total investment of
the new company is 29.99 million U.S. dollars, of which 41 percent
is funded by Nippon Electric Co. Ltd., a major semiconductor
producer in the world.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Hua Hong IC Design Co., Ltd. controls 40 percent of the
shares, and the remaining 19 percent belong to two Sino-Japanese
joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the new operation, Beijing Hua Hong NEC IC
Design Co., Ltd., is another significant step to narrow the gap
between China and the world's advanced level in electronic
information industry.
</P>
<P>
The new company is expected to turn out 200 integrated circuit
designs annually, and offer Shanghai Hua Hong NEC Microelectronics
Co., Ltd. orders of up to 20,000 eight-inch silicon chips.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Hua Hong NEC is the core of Project 909. It is
funded by Shanghai Hua Hong Microelectronics Co. Ltd. and NEC with
an investment of 10 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Its assembly line will start to produce eight-inch chips in
Feb. 1999, seven months ahead of schedule.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai joint venture is the largest Sino-Japanese funded
enterprise next to the Baoshan Iron and Steel Group located in
Shanghai.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaoning to Continue to Push Forward SOE Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The northeastern province of
Liaoning, China's leading old industrial base whose ill-managed
state sector is overstaffed but not efficient, will continue
advancing the reform of state-owned enterprises and displacing
laid-off workers by improving social security system.
</P>
<P>
These remarks were made here today by top Liaoning officials,
including Governor Zhang Guoguang and executive vice-governor Guo
Tingbiao, at a press conference hosted by the ongoing First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress, China's top
legislature.
</P>
<P>
Zhang noted that as an old industrial base developed in the
1950s when China practiced strict central planning in enterprise
management, Liaoning, where 10 percent of the country's large and
medium-sized state enterprises are based, has heavy historical
burdens in the shift toward a socialist market economic system.
</P>
<P>
While striving to improve the management and performance of
large state enterprises, he said, Liaoning this year will further
ease the control over medium-sized and small enterprises in the
state sector and promote common development of multiple economic
elements through various means.
</P>
<P>
In the face of increasing layoffs of state-owned enterprises,
Zhang said, governments at all levels across Liaoning have
intensified their efforts to improve the social security system
for the laid-off and retired workers.
</P>
<P>
"Now 98 percent of the workers in large and medium-sized state
enterprises in Liaoning have been covered by various insurances,
while all the 14 cities across the province have established
complete systems to help the extremely needy workers," he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
