<HEADLINE> S'pore Internet Providers Required to Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Internet service
providers will be required by law to offer parents a way of
weeding out on-line pornography by the end of this year,
Information and the Arts Minister George Yeo said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in Parliament, the Minister said that the Internet
service providers would, according to the law, install a filter in
their servers to block access to undesirable sites.
</P>
<P>
"All Internet service providers will be required by regulation
to provide parents with the option," he said.
</P>
<P>
The "cleaner, more sanitized" Internet service will be built in
at the server level, he stressed, citing Cyber Patrol and Nanny
Net as examples of such filtering programs. The Minister noted
that children were now knowledgeable about gaining access even to
blocked sites.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore Broadcasting Authority (SBA) has banned some 100
websites that promote pornography, violence, and racial or
religious hatred. 
</P>
