<HEADLINE> Malaysian, Vietnamese Leaders Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam has agreed to the
promotion of intra-ASEAN trade using their own currencies,
Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was expressed by Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong at a meeting with him, Mahathir told reporters after the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, together with some other countries of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), has been pushing for the use
of regional currencies in trade between ASEAN members after their
currencies have declined dramatically against the U.S. dollar
since July last year.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said the Vietnamese president had also requested him
to explain the economic crisis faced by Malaysia and other ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said they also discussed the ASEAN summit to be held
in Hanoi, the forthcoming Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) and the Asia
Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) meeting.
</P>
<P>
Tran Duc Luong arrived here Monday afternoon for a three-day
visit, the first by a Vietnamese head of state since the two
countries established diplomatic ties in 1973.  
</P>
