<HEADLINE> Malaysia: No Need for Economic Union With Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian International Trade
and
Industry Minister Datuk Seri Rafidah Aziz said here on Monday that
there is no necessity for a Malaysia-Singapore Economic Union.
</P>
<P>
There is already the ASEAN (Association of South East Asian
Nations) Free Trade Area (AFTA) with "a lot of bilaterals going
on," the minister was quoted by Singapore television as saying.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah made the remarks after a dialogue session with
Singapore businessmen. The dialogue session was jointly organized
by the Singapore Confederation of Industries and the Malaysian
High Commission in Singapore and sponsored by Maybank.
</P>
<P>
However, Rafidah urged Singaporean and Malaysian businessmen to
seek more areas of cooperation rather than compete head-on on the
world market.
</P>
<P>
She said both sides can improve their market shares by
cooperating instead of remaining stagnant by competing against
each other.
</P>
<P>
The chemical sector is one area where Malaysia and Singapore
can avoid competition, the minister said, adding that competition
in this instance will only lead to huge investments and
over-capacity.
</P>
<P>
Rafidah also said companies in Singapore should consider
cooperating with Malaysian investors in human resources
development such as training trainers, setting up skill-training
institutes and other collaborative efforts.
</P>
<P>
"There is still at present a high level of interdependence
between the economies of the two countries, including in the
manufacturing sector," she added.
</P>
<P>
The two countries would emerge from the current economic
turmoil on an even stronger footing if they work closely in
developing their economies, she said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
