<HEADLINE> Sandstorm Hits Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The sandstorm originated in Egypt
is covering the whole of Cyprus Monday, but no air traffic was
affected.
</P>
<P>
Loizos Hadjioannou, a senior meteorological department
official, said the sandstorm was caused by atmospheric pressure
activity and was transferred to Cyprus by strong southern winds.
</P>
<P>
The storm began to affect the island at around 0200 local time
(2400 GMT), according to the official.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the atmosphere to clear after midday either because
of a change in the direction of the wind or rain," Hadjioannou
added.
</P>
<P>
The sandstorm in Egypt forced British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook, heading for Egypt on a three-day tour of the region, to
make a stop-over in Cyprus Sunday evening as the Cairo airport
was closed.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary is scheduled to meet Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak later Monday within the framework of a Middle East
tour aimed at helping revive the stalled Middle East peace
process.
</P>
<P>
The civil aviation official said visibility at Larnaca Airport
is about 700 meters and flights to and from Cyprus have not been
affected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
