<HEADLINE> WFP Urged to Restart Food Supplies to Somalis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Rahanwein communities of
Southwestern Somalia Monday urged World Food Program (WFP) to
resume its relief food supplies to the flood-ridden areas in
Somalia after attacks on a relief mission aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The World Food Program (WFP) has discontinued its foodstuff
airdrops to flood stricken Somalis in Bay, middle and lower Jubba
regions after its aircraft were attacked three days ago.
</P>
<P>
The Rahanwein officials have portrayed that the firing upon
the WFP airplane that transported the dry food to the flood
displaced families near Sakow Weyn village was an unfortunate and
isolated incident perpetrated by irresponsible armed gangs.
</P>
<P>
Humanitarian affairs secretary of the Rahanwein Resistance
Army Sheikh Qasim Ibrahim Nur, speaking to reporters in Mogadishu
here Monday, said two of the gunmen who fired upon the relief
airplane were caught Sunday and put into custody while the rest
are still being hunted down in nearby villages.
</P>
<P>
Qasim said the perpetrators of the attack will be severely
dealt with under the Islamic laws of the local Sharia court.
</P>
<P>
He said the elders are now in control of the situation and a
peaceful environment is created for the smooth resumption of the
humanitarian supplies of food aid by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Qasim called on the WFP to recommence its noble activities in
which thousands of somalis have been saved from hunger and
starvation following the disastrous floods that hit these regions
late last year.
</P>
<P>
As the floods began receding in many places in Southern
Somalia, thousands of people are still in desperate need for
humanitarian help since they were still dislodged from their home
places, he said.
</P>
<P>
The flood affected families are less likely to return to their
places of origin in the near future unless seeds and three months
food ration are provided to each family for self-sustenance
project in the near future, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
More than 2,000 people are believed to have died and over
60,000 hectares of farmland were erased while nearly 40,000 head
of goats, cattle and camels were also washed away by the floods
which have been the most serious for more than 40 years in the
history of Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
