<HEADLINE> Israel Refuses EU Mediation Role if Cook Visits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel threatened Monday to
deny the European Union (EU) as a mediator in the Middle East
peace process if British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook insists on
visiting Har Homa in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu, continued to criticize Cook's plan to visit the
controversial Har Homa site, where Israel is building a Jewish
settlement.
</P>
<P>
He told Israel Radio that just as the Israeli premier should
not hurry to meet Northern Irish separatist Sinn Fein leader Gerry
Adams during his visit to London, Cook should not meet in
Jerusalem with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) Minister of
Jerusalem Affairs Faisal Husseini and leaders of Israeli peace
movement Peace Now.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country is holding EU's rotating presidency, is
due here on Tuesday as part of his upcoming Middle Eastern
tour that also includes Palestine, Egypt, Jordan, Lebanon and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan denied Israel is threatening to remove the EU
from the peace process over Cook's Har Homa visit, but he
stressed that the EU could not serve as a mediator in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process because of its support to the
Palestinian positions. He added that the EU could still play a
role in helping advance the multilateral Middle East talks and
in providing financial aid to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Israel began the construction of Har Homa settlement in
March last year, leading to a seven-month suspension of
Israeli-Palestinian peace talks. The PNA charged Israel for
violating the Oslo accords which demand both sides refrain from
changing the status quo of Jerusalem, whose fate should be
settled through permanent talks.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strong opposition by Israel, Cook reportedly has
dropped his plan to visit the Har Homa site with the escort
of Husseini.
</P>
<P>
Cook's decision to visit Har Homa has also sparked angry
protests from Israeli rightwingers, who vandalized the British
Consulate in Jerusalem by painting slogans on its walls
denouncing Cook as "an antisemite." The consulate expressed regret
over the acts, saying the purpose of Cook's visit was to advance
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government was also upset by the reports that Cook
would launch a new initiative to break the deadlock in the
Israeli-Palestinian talks by demanding Israel carry out 15-20
percent further pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israeli government, which is only willing to redeploy troops
from 9 percent of West Bank in the second further
redeployment, has said it would not compromise on any issues
over its security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
