<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regions Along Yangtze River Take Economic Lead in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The regions along the Yangtze
River, China's longest river, have recorded rapid economic growth
in the past several years as a result of the correct economic
strategy adopted by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, the Chinese government decided to place
emphasis on the development of Shanghai, China's largest city at
the mouth of the Yangtze, so as to promote the overall economic
growth for all regions along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
A series of major decisions have since been made, such as
the opening-up and development of the Pudong New Area in Shanghai
and the start of construction of the Three Gorges Dam, the world's
largest hydropower project.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, a dozen ports and cities by the Yangtze River,
including Zhangjiagang, Nanjing, Wuhan and Yichang, have been
announced to be open to the outside world, while Chongqing, a
major industrial center in southwest China, has been upgraded to
be the country's fourth municipality directly under the central
government after Beijing, Tianjin and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that in recent years, the economic growth for
the seven provinces and two municipalities along the Yangtze,
namely Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Anhui, Jiangxi, Hubei, Hunan, Sichuan,
Shanghai and Chongqing, has been much higher than the national
average.
</P>
<P>
The overall Gross Domestic Product (GDP) for these regions now
accounts for one third of China's total, and the amount of foreign
capital invested in these regions has surged to 30 percent of the
country's total from only 10 percent six years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to Huang Ju, Party secretary of Shanghai and a deputy
to the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), China's top
legislature, in session here since early March, Shanghai has used
25 billion US dollars of foreign capital and scored an average
annual GDP growth of 13.8 percent over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Zhejiang, one of Shanghai's neighboring
provinces, has scored a more astounding high growth of 19
percent a year in the past six years.
</P>
<P>
The GDP of Chongqing, which became a municipality a year ago,
reached 137.5 billion yuan (15.57 billion US dollars) last year,
up by 11.5 percent over the previous year, said NPC deputy Zhang
Delin, who is Party secretary of Chongqing.
</P>
<P>
Economists said the strong momentum shown by regions along the
Yangtze in their opening-up and development over the past six
years indicates a most promising future for these regions'
economic growth in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"We're striving to turn Pudong into a bridge linking Shanghai,
the Yangtze River delta and even the entire Yangtze River economic
zone to the rest of the world," said Deputy Hu Wei, deputy
director of the Management Committee of the Pudong New Area.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Jiang Zhuping, governor of Hubei Province, which is
along the middle reaches of the Yangtze River, suggested that all
regions along the Yangtze further pool their efforts and economic
strength and build a "Yangtze River Economic Community". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
