<HEADLINE> Chinese Firm Sues U.S. Company for Copyright Infringement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Answering the New York state court's request to provide
evidence of Chinese Star's product value, the company recently had
the brand evaluated by a Beijing University business research
institute which claimed that the trademark is worth 1.22 billion
yuan (140 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
With the Chinese Star case, SunTendy becomes the first Chinese
information technology company to go to an overseas court to
defend its intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
Dong Baolin, an official engaged in the administration of
trademarks in China, said, "In the era of information technology,
the intellectual property rights protection is often linked to the
matter of safeguarding 'national interests'."
</P>
<P>
Since its debut on the Chinese market in 1992, Chinese Star has
become a leader in China's fledging software industry by providing
solutions to handling Chinese language software in an
English-dominated computer environment.
</P>
<P>
Having survived the impacts from rivals such as Microsoft
Windows' Chinese edition, other Chinese-built peer products, and
rampant piracy, Chinese Star sold 250,000 copies in 1997 with a
net profit of 32 million yuan (3.9 million U.S. dollars) for
SunTendy.  
</P>
