<HEADLINE> Australian FM to Visit U.S., S. Korea and Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian Foreign Affairs
Minister Alexander Downer will travel to the United States
Wednesday to discuss the Asian economic crisis, focusing on
problems facing Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
After a four-day stay in the U.S., the minister will fly to
Seoul and Tokyo to have further discussions with South Korean and
Japanese leaders on the Asian economic crisis and Indonesian
situation during his nine-day trip.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released Monday, Downer said he would have talks
with the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the World Bank on
the current financial turmoil in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"These talks are part of a continuing dialogue which the
Australian government has been vigorously pursuing," he said,
adding "as both a contributor to the IMF package for Indonesia and
a neighbor of that country, with great strategic interests at
stake in Indonesia's economic and political stability, we
naturally want to see further agreement quickly reached between
Indonesia and the IMF."
</P>
<P>
Downer said, "I will also have discussions on Indonesia and the
Asian economic crisis in both Seoul and Tokyo."
</P>
<P>
He said he will use his visit to South Korea to establish early
contact with south Korea's new administration and meet president
Kim Dae-Jung.
</P>
<P>
Australia welcomed the progress south Korea had made in
implementing the conditions of its IMF bailout, a package
Australia had contributed to, he added.
</P>
<P>
In Tokyo, he said, he would meet with senior ministers there,
as "the key roles of both countries have in contributing to a
resolution of the crisis and Japan's status as our largest market
and major source of investment, the visit is very important and
timely," he said. 
</P>
