<HEADLINE> Cook Arrives in Egypt on Mideast Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook arrived here Monday noon at the first leg of his Middle East
trip aimed at helping break the deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Cook will meet with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and other
government officials.
</P>
<P>
The British foreign secretary, accompanied by European Union
Middle East envoy Miguel Moratinos, will discuss with his
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa a European Union (EU) proposal
aimed at pushing forward the Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
The proposal calls for Palestinian commitment to Israel's
security demands, and urges Israel to implement a significant
redeployment, halt settlement expansion and support the
Palestinian economy.
</P>
<P>
The talks will also deal with bilateral relations between Egypt
and Britain which currently holds the rotating EU presidency.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace process has been deadlocked since
March 1997 after Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement
in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Cook's tour also includes Jordan, Israel, the Palestinian
self-rule areas, Syria and Lebanon. He was scheduled to arrive
here Sunday night, but was forced to stop over in Cyprus due to a
sandstorm that hit Egypt, Lebanon, Cyprus and other regional
states.
</P>
<P>
Trade volume between Britain and Egypt amounts to one billion
U.S. dollars annually. Britain is Egypt's second largest foreign
investor with investments standing at one billion sterlings (1.67
billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
