<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Population Expected to Peak in Mid-21st Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China's population will begin to
decrease after it reaches its peak in the mid-21st century,
according to the State Family Planning Commission (SFPC).
</P>
<P>
Experts predicted that the peak number will be about 1.6
billion.
</P>
<P>
China will try to control its population within 1.3 billion by
the year 2000 and 1.4 billion by 2010, according to a plan set
forward by the SFPC today at an ongoing National Conference on
Family Planning in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
In tandem with population control, China will try to reduce the
incidence of defects in newborn babies and provide better
reproductive health care for the people of child-bearing age,
according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
The problems of an aging population and the unbalanced gender
ratio among newborns in some areas will also be resolved, the plan
said.
</P>
<P>
The population will maintain a low growth rate by 2021, and the
people's health and education level will be greatly improved, it
predicted.
</P>
<P>
China's population will begin to drop gradually in the middle
of the 21st century when the population structure becomes more
rational and the people conscientiously practise family planning,
the plan said.
</P>
<P>
The country's birth rate was 16.57 per 1,000 in 1997, 1.67
permillage points lower than that of 1992. The total population,
including the people in Hong Kong, reached 1.243 billion at the
end of 1997, according to the SFPC.
</P>
<P>
Experts said China's population will continue to increase by an
average of 13 million a year in the next two or three years,
although the population growth rate keeps dropping.
</P>
<P>
In family planning, China will continue to put the stress on
the rural areas, especially those in central and west China
provinces, and will improve family planning management among
transients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
