<HEADLINE> Indonesia Calls ASEM Very Important to ASEAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said here Monday that the Second Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM)
is very important to ASEAN member countries including Indonesia
because it will discuss economic cooperation between Asia and
Europe.
</P>
<P>
Newly-elected Vice President B. J. Habibie will represent
President Soeharto at the ASEM to be held in London between April
1 and 4, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas, who will also attend the meeting, also stressed the
importance of stabilizing the country's currency, the rupiah, and
settling the private sector's foreign debts.
</P>
<P>
The two issues are high on Indonesia's priority list to pave
the way for economic recovery, he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, along with other countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), has been hit by a monetary crisis
since July last year, with the rupiah having lost about 80 percent
of its value against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Economists held that the private sector's foreign debts, which
account for 60 percent of the country's total foreign borrowing of
about 140 billion dollars, is one of the main causes of the
monetary crisis in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Alatas also hoped that the International Monetary Fund (IMF),
which has promised a 43 billion dollar bailout package to
Indonesia and asked the country to carry out economic and
financial reforms, would be more flexible in the implementation of
some aspects of the IMF program.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, Myanmar, Laos, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
