<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.8 Billion-Year-Old Brown Algae Fossils Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered more than 120 pieces of 1.88 billion-year-old
multicellular algae fossils, the earliest record of multicellular
life on Earth. The fossils were found in the eastern part of
Yanshan Mountain in northern China.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that the discovery of the fossils are of
great importance to the research of early evolution of life on
Earth and ancient geological environments.
</P>
<P>
It has been generally acknowledged that the geological record
of the appearance of the multicellular organism was 900 million
years old. The recent discovery by Chinese archeologists shifts
the record of multicellular organisms to 1.88 billion years ago.
</P>
<P>
The fossils were located in sandwich structures of rock, and
more than 300 brown algae were found on each fossil. The algae are
in three types: round, oval and spiral-shaped.
</P>
<P>
Some of the fossils became curled and smaller after they were
taken from the rocks and were exposed to the air, indicating
activated changes in the organisms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
