<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Commission Approves Securities Investment Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese securities investment
funds -- Kaiyuan and Jintai -- have been approved by the China
Securities Regulatory Commission to begin issuing at the stock
exchange on March 23.
</P>
<P>
As a new kind of securities in China, the Kaiyuan and Jintai
funds would be issued equivalent to 2 billion yuan (240 million
U.S. dollars) each with a deposit term of 15 years. The Industrial
and Commercial Bank of China will be the trustee for the
investment funds.
</P>
<P>
The two funds will also apply for listing and trading at stock
exchanges after being issued. Twenty percent of the basic assets
would be invested in state bonds, while the remaining 80 percent
would go to stocks in open circulation of the country.
</P>
<P>
The securities investment fund, in which investors would
commonly share interests and risks, has become popular overseas.
</P>
<P>
The fund will help absorb more individual capital into the
stock market and turn savings into investments to better serve the
reform of state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Medium and small investors can spread investment risks through
management of money matters by experts, while the development of
securities investment funds will change the situation that medium
and small investors constitute too large a proportion in stock
exchanges, and make the securities markets more stable.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
