<HEADLINE> Kuwait's Crown Prince Asked to Form New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah asked Crown Prince Sheikh Saad Al-Abdullah
Al-Salem Al-Sabah to nominate new members of the cabinet after it
resigned Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The Emir instructed the crown prince and the outgoing ministers
whose resignations were accepted by the Emir to carry on their
duties to handle emergency affairs pending formation of a new
government, a statement from the Emir's office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The resignation came following members of the parliament
maintained their intention to press ahead with a no-confidence
vote against Minister of Information Sheikh Saud Nasser
Al-Sabah over display of controversial books at the Arab Book
Fair last month.
</P>
<P>
The resignation has been seen as a government attempt to abort
a vote of no-confidence against him.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member cabinet was formed upon an Emiri decree
following general elections on October 15, 1996.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait saw the most serious clash between the National
Assembly and government last Tuesday on grilling the information
minister as the crown prince strongly criticized some
parliamentary members for trying to abuse democracy in the small
Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 Islamic members in the parliament submitted a
motion of no-confidence against the information minister on March
10.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary members supporting the motion have spent the last
few days frantically lobbying more back-up from their fellow
members. It was reported that as many as 30 members were ready to
vote for the motion.
</P>
<P>
Members of the cabinet submitted their resignations to show
solidarity with the information minister.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saad sternly warned the opposition political group last
Tuesday that their activities could put the country's future at
stake, explaining that his government would not be lenient with
those who were trying to undermine the country's security.
</P>
</TEXT>
