<HEADLINE> S. Africa Prepares for Chemical Weapon Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Armscor, South Africa's
state-owned arms producer, is gearing up for chemical weapons
threat, local daily Business Day reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The threat of chemical weapons changing from purely a military
form to one in which they are unleashed by terrorists or fanatics
emphasized the need for research into better chemical defensive
method, Armscor's executive chairman Ron Haywood said at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Haywood said Tokyo's recent crude chemical attack carried out
by a Japanese cult, which killed 12 people and sickened 5,000,
emphasized the need for research on trace quantities of chemical
agents and adequate protection of personnel.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks at the opening of Protechnik, a chemical
defense research institution based in Pretoria, which was wholly
owned by Armscor but self-sufficient.
</P>
<P>
The institution is the only South African firm which can
synthesize enough scheduled chemicals for testing and evaluation
of chemical defense equipment.
</P>
<P>
Protechnik is subject to regular international inspections,
with one successfully done at the new site recently. Haywood said
the move to the new site facilitated the functioning of a
sophisticated laboratory utilizing advanced computer-controlled
equipment and electronic communication.
</P>
<P>
Among some of its other achievements, Haywood said Protechnik
had established an internationally recognized quality assurance
system and also took part in proficiency test. This was done to
enable it to become the Organization for the Prohibition of
Chemical Weapons designate for Africa.
</P>
<P>
Also, he said, Protechnik had developed a nuclear biological
and chemical filter system for the South Africa-made G-6
artillery which had been exported to several countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
