<HEADLINE> Howard on Australia Attracting Overseas Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister John Howard said
Monday that his government had an aim to strengthen the factors
which underpin Australia's attractiveness as an investment
destination.
</P>
<P>
"We are committed to an ongoing program to remove the
constraints on strong sustained growth and to enhance the capacity
of the Australian economy to be competitive in a global context,"
Howard said.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the World Economic Forum in Melbourne, He said,
his government had an "overriding aim" to deliver an annual
economic growth rate of over four percent between 2000 and 2010.
</P>
<P>
And it was his government's intention to make Australia second
only to Tokyo as a regional financial center by 2000, the
Australian Associated Press reported from Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
Howard also told the forum his government had laid the
foundations that would allow Australia the best possible chance of
riding out "the flow on effects of the troubles in Asia".
</P>
<P>
In the speech Howard said the government had already laid the
basis for the development of an integrated and world competitive
financial services sector.
</P>
<P>
"In a global environment where capital is increasingly mobile
the key to Australia's attractiveness as an investment location
will continue to be the strength of our economic foundations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Expanding our export base and building a strong export culture
in both goods and services markets are key priorities for policy
making by my government," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the world moved toward the new millennium, the government
was committed to building a community in which the interests of
people rather than those of technology prevailed, Howard said.
</P>
</TEXT>
