<HEADLINE> Nigerian Exporters Receive $3.6M as Incentives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian exporters received 303
million Naira (about 3.6 million U.S. Dollars) as export
incentives in 1997, the Nigerian Export Promotion Council (NEPC)
has said.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Yuguda Usman, chairman of the NEPC, was quoted by
Monday's Daily Champion as saying that the incentives were funded
through the NEPC's Duty Draw Back Refund scheme and the Export
Expansion Grant.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the NEPC now applies the uniform rate of
four percent of foreign exchange proceed repatriated as basis for
the disbursement of export expansion grant.
</P>
<P>
The chairman disclosed that new incentive schemes are being
fine-tuned to take off next year.
</P>
<P>
Usman commended the government's motion to promote non-oil
export and canvassed for more funds to encourage export.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the 13 percent increase in Nigeria's non-oil
export from 108 billion Naira (about 1.3 billion Dollars) in 1996
to 123 billion Naira (about 15 billion Dollars) was possible
largely due to the incentive schemes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
