<HEADLINE> S. African Transport Workers on Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Hundreds of road and
freight industry workers went on strike here Monday following a
labor-management deadlock over wage hikes and working condition
improvements, South Africa Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The workers gathered at Library Gardens in downtown
Johannesburg Monday morning for a march to the City Hall, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Seven transport unions, which represent more than 40,000 truck
drivers nationwide, were organizing rallies in the country's
major cities Monday, said spokesman of the Transport and General
Workers Union Thulani Dlamini.
</P>
<P>
The unions reportedly rejected employers' final subsistence
allowances and their offer on minimum wages ranging from 11.5 to
18 percent.
</P>
<P>
Dlamini said the unions would approach the Commission for
Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration, a statutory body, to
help appoint a mediator between the unions and the Road Freight
Employers' Association (RFEA).
</P>
<P>
A Star paper report quoted the employers' association as
saying it could lose millions of Rands in business, as any strike
in the industry was bound to "affect it substantially." 
</P>
</TEXT>
