<HEADLINE> 5 Teenagers Killed by Bomb in Southern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Five Iraqi teenagers were killed
Monday by a bomb left over from the 1991 Gulf War in the southern
port city of Basra, 560 kilometers south of Baghdad, the Iraqi
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
An official in the civilian defense sector said that the bomb
exploded in Basra's al-Hussein Quarter, claiming the lives of the
five teenagers.
</P>
<P>
The official, whose name is not known, said that staff from the
civilian defense sector had earlier defused three bombs found at
the scene of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
Monday's explosion is the second so far this year in
Basra. One bomb exploded on January 25 in Abul Khasib District,
killing 21 women and children. 
</P>
