<HEADLINE> World Bank Expects Malaysian Economy to Recover Soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 16 (Xinhua) -- World Bank Senior Vice
President and chief economist Joseph Stiglitz said here Monday
that the Malaysian economy has prospects for a quick recovery as
the stock and foreign exchange markets have stabilized.
</P>
<P>
"The fact that the markets have stabilized is good news and is
(the) basis for prospects of a quick recovery to the economic
situation here," he told reporters after meeting Malaysian Deputy
Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz praised Malaysia for having undertaken measures before
the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has the good fortune of having undertaken a number of
actions over several years preceding the present situation, which
put it in a much stronger stead than many other countries, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This meant that its exposure to some of the risks faced by
other countries is much less, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The state of the economy in Malaysia is clearly one of the
strongest points within the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz's visit to Malaysia is part of the World Bank's
on-going dialogue with the countries of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and its continuing assessment of
the region's economic conditions in view of the crisis facing the
region.
</P>
<P>
Describing his talks with Anwar as "very fruitful, enjoyable
and interesting," Stiglitz said the discussion with Anwar was a
continuing dialogue on a range of economic issues, including
various measures that the government has already undertaken to
strengthen the economy.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz said the World Bank's discussion with regional
economies focused on the "financial sector, corporate governance
and most importantly, the social safety net."
</P>
<P>
He said the Malaysian government has already undertaken
measures to ensure that the most vulnerable people are not
adversely affected.
</P>
<P>
"We are continuing discussions about any other way that we at
the (World) Bank can help either through financial or technical
assistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the World Bank's forecast of Malaysia's
economic growth in 1998, Stiglitz said: "I don't have our numbers
for 1998 at this point."
</P>
<P>
Anwar said Monday on another occasion that Malaysia's growth
projection of between 4 and 5 percent for 1998, which was revised
last December from an earlier forecast of 7 percent, is no longer
realistic and should be revised again to a lower figure, taking
into account the most recent trade and economic statistics.
</P>
<P>
On a soft loan offered by the World Bank as announced by Anwar
during the weekend, Stiglitz said the issue is currently being
discussed actively. The soft loan, according to Anwar, is to be
used for rural development and poverty eradication programs in
Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz said that over the last 35 years, Southeast Asia has
been the most successful region in terms of reducing poverty and
improving living standards.
</P>
<P>
He was of the view that the present financial turmoil is "just
a short interruption in the rapid growth" of the region.
</P>
<P>
He said the World Bank's objective is to get the economies back
on the growth track and to ensure that the most disadvantaged in
the society do not suffer too much.
</P>
<P>
Like other Asian countries, Malaysia has been severely affected
by the regional financial crisis triggered by the devaluation of
the Thai baht in early July last year.
</P>
<P>
The most affected are Indonesia, Thailand and South Korea,
which have received International Monetary Fund (IMF) aid
exceeding 100 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, due to its better economic position, has been able to
evade the IMF's package but nevertheless has taken IMF-style
reforms in an effort to ensure loans to productive sectors such as
manufacturing and agriculture.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
