<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Firm Sues U.S. Company for Copyright Infringement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The manufacturer of Chinese Star,
the country's first software providing solutions to processing
Chinese characters in a Microsoft Windows environment, has sued a
U.S. company for infringing upon its copyright to a state court in
New York with a demand for 5 million U.S. dollars in compensation.
</P>
<P>
According to a chief manager of Beijing Founder SunTendy
Software Technology Ltd., the New York court has agreed to
consider the lawsuit against New York City-based Alestron Inc. for
possible infringement upon the Beijing company's rights.
</P>
<P>
The manager who invented Chinese Star claimed that the software
is worth 1.22 billion yuan (140 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
SunTendy's market manager, Zhou Mi, said that his company and
Alestron failed in a recent talk initiated by the U.S. firm to act
as sales agent for Chinese Star in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Zhou said that Alestron registered itself on the World Wide Web
under a Web site name "extremely similar to that owned by the
Chinese Star."
</P>
<P>
"What's more," he said, "under the name of Chinese Star,
Alestron is promoting those products which are competing with
Chinese Star's products."
</P>
<P>
Last September SunTendy hired a U.S. lawyer and formally filed
suit against Alestron in New York.
</P>
<P>
Before and after taking its action, SunTendy tried to contact
Alestron, but received no "substantial response," Zhou said.
"Their only visible reaction was to erase all contents on their
Web home page."
</P>
<P>
At present, the Web site "http://www. Chinese-Star.com" owned
by Alestron is blank.
</P>
<P>
The SunTendy manager said that his company "is sure to win. It
is just a matter of how much compensation we shall get," Zhou
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
