<HEADLINE> Share Prices Close Mixed on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Share prices closed mixed in
thin trading on the Singapore market, while the benchmark Straits
Times Industrials Index (STII) gained 6.16 points to close at
1,604.79 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that the market sentiment was affected by regional
uncertainty and a recent crop of poor corporate earnings and most
investors were thus kept sidelined.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the STII ended higher, helped by light fund
buying mainly in newspaper monopoly Singapore Press Holdings Ltd.
</P>
<P>
Further upside of the market hinges on whether liquidity from
foreign funds increases, they said.
</P>
<P>
The total market volume stood at 181.95 million units, worth
247.46 million Singapore dollars (about 153.7 million U.S.
dollars). Declines led advances by 198 to 127, while 287 other
counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Renong Bhd was the most actively traded stock as it registered
a turnover of 11.39 million units. It was followed by M. Resources
which had 7.98 million shares traded. Datapulse was next with 7.85
million shares changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Thai Prime Fund led the gainers of the day as it rose by 40
cents to finish at 5.4 Singapore dollars. Asean Fund increased by
35 cents to end at 8.4 Singapore dollars, while Asia Pacific was
up by 32 cents to close at 5.1 Singapore dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, SIA (Singapore Airlines) Foreign and Nat Kap
shared the top spot on the losers' list as each of them declined
by 30 cents to end at 11.4 Singapore dollars and 0.6 Singapore
dollar respectively. Creative 50 and the OCBC (Overseas Chinese
Banking Corporation) Foreign fell by 20 cents each to close at
36.8 and 8.5 Singapore dollars respectively. NST lost 16 cents to
finish at 2.09 Singapore dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
