<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Tibetan Art Exhibition Opens in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A six-day China's Tibetan Art
Exhibition opened at the Birendra International Convention Center
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Nepali Prime Minister Surya Bahadur Thapa, Minister for Youth,
Sports and Culture Sharat Singh Bhandari, Finance Minister
Rabindra Nath Sharma and some foreign diplomats were among some
400 people attending the opening ceremony of the exhibition
sponsored by the Chinese Embassy in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Chinese Ambassador Zhang Jiuhuan said this is an
art exhibition from "the Roof of the World." With diligence and
wisdom, the Tibetan people living in this miracle land for
generations have created their splendid art with unique charms.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, thanks to the concern and support of the
central government and the Tibet Autonomous Region government, the
Tibetan art has been further enriched and developed from the basis
of its tradition, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Tibet Autonomous Region of China and the Kingdom of Nepal are
linked by common mountains and rivers, and have stood together
both in good and bad times," he said, adding "For centuries, there
have been frequent exchanges of visits and close cooperation."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the stability and development of Tibet, including
the prosperity of the Tibet art, are also due to the valuable
support and help from Nepal," the ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that the art exhibition will further
strengthen the exchanges, understanding, friendship and
cooperation between China and Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Minister Bhandari said the exhibition provided a very rare
opportunity for critics and art lovers to see and enjoy the beauty
of paintings, tangkas, sculpture, jewelry costumes and artifacts
from the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
"Such exhibitions are always welcome as they enrich our
knowledge about Tibetan art and craft and promote mutual
understanding and friendship between the peoples of Nepal and
Tibet Autonomous Region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Thapa said on the occasion that the bilateral
relations between Nepal and China have always been marked with
friendship, cordiality and mutual cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"Because of our geographical proximity, Nepal has been enjoying
most cordial relationship with the Tibet Autonomous Region of
China since time immemorial," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes that bilateral relations are greatly
consolidated by promoting understanding of each other's culture at
the people's level.
</P>
<P>
On display are about 100 pictures and some 500 objects relating
to animal husbandry, agriculture, dress and personal adornment,
tangka and masks in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
Tangka is the most common traditional art products of Tibetan
Buddhism, which depicts a wide range of subjects including
historical events, biographies, religious doctrines, Tibetan
natural conditions and social customs, folklore and mythologies.
</P>
<P>
Tibetan folk songs and dances were also performed on the
occasion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
