<HEADLINE> 3 Muslim Rebels Killed in Clash in South Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Three members of the rebel Moro
Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) were killed over the weekend
during a series of skirmishes with a former Muslim rebel group in
a southern Philippine province, the Philippine News Agency said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mastura Sultan, a commander of the Moro National Liberation
Front (MNLF), was quoted as saying Monday that the MILF and the
MNLF clashed last weekend in Midsayap town of Cotabato Province in
Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Sultan said the conflicts erupted when the MILF guerrillas
encroached upon the MNLF-controlled village of Labas to impose
revolutionary taxes on its residents who had long resisted the
taxation.
</P>
<P>
MNLF leaders in Midsayap town have urged government troops to
intervene in the recent conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, speaking over a local radio station, Ghadzali
Jaafar, MILF vice chair for political affairs, confirmed the
reported skirmishes, but he downplayed them as a "petty
misunderstanding" between members of the two Moro fronts.
</P>
<P>
Jaafar said he would bring the incident before a joint
MNLF-MILF committee for an immediate investigation.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction of the larger MNLF, is now the
strongest anti-government force in the country with an estimated
membership of 12,000 after the MNLF signed a peace treaty with the
government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, which has refused to be included in the
MNLF-government peace treaty, began its own peace talks with the
government in early 1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-Owned Enterprises Lead Jan-Feb Export Figures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned enterprises
exported products valued at 13.46 billion US dollars for the first
two months of this year, up 10.5 percent on the 1996 period, with
the sector accounting for 54.2 percent of the nation's total
export volume, according to statistics released by the General
Administration of Customs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, exports of collective enterprises climbed 41.6
percent to 690 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, state-owned enterprises recorded a 2.6 percent decline
in imports to 7.17 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Foreign-funded enterprises imported goods valued at 10.05
billion US dollars, up 1.4 percent. The figure for equipment
imported as part of investments was 2.36 billion US dollars, down
10.1 percent on the 1997 figure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
