<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group Making Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The 31st meeting of the
Sino-Portuguese Joint Liaison Group (JLG) reached agreement on
some issues and discussed others on Macao's transfer of power
today in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Both sides studied civil servants' status and the laws of Macao
as well as the use of Chinese as an official language, saying that
they would continue to work on these issues.
</P>
<P>
Transition-related issues such as pensions for civil servants,
franchises straddling 1999 and the transfer of Macao's government
assets were also discussed at the four-day meeting that ended
March 13.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to further negotiate on issues of
retaining a Portuguese language school in Macao after 1999, as
well as the transfer of archives and nationality.
</P>
<P>
Agreements were signed on Macao's continuous participation in
such international organizations as the International Statistical
Institute, the Organization of Labor Health and Security of the
Asia-Pacific Region, the Football Federation of Schools of Asia,
and the Sports Federation of Schools of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also agreed on airline links between Macao and South
Africa, and reached a common understanding on the continuous
application of seven international conventions on labor and
maritime affairs in Macao.
</P>
<P>
Passports issued by the Macao government for Portuguese
nationals overseas will lapse two years after the
transition. according to the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both sides also exchanged views on listing new subjects on the
JLG agenda put forward by China and Portugal on Macao's transfer
of power.
</P>
<P>
The 32nd meeting of the Sino-Portuguese JLG was set for June 30
in Macao.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
