<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Seminar Begins on Financing in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A five-day regional workshop began
here Monday on rural and micro-financial products and services in
Asia, with the aim of disseminating innovative concepts,
strategies and models of poverty alleviation through rural credit
and micro-finance.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, sponsored by the Asia Pacific Rural and
Agricultural Credit Association, the International Fund for
Agricultural Development and Bangladesh Bank, will concentrate on
the design of financial products and provisions of financial
services for the rural poor.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the workshop, Governor of Bangladesh Bank Lutfur
Rahman Sarkar said the approach of providing micro-credit to the
poor through official, private and non-governmental organizations
has gained ground, as the existing financial system could not
ensure the poor the right of access to credit.
</P>
<P>
Per-capita GDP in Bangladesh is quite low and the distribution
system in the country is skewed, he noted. Thus both productive
and income-generating activities must be encouraged among the poor
through the provision of financing and other inputs.
</P>
<P>
"This is expected to result in increased production and an
egalitarian distribution of income," he added.
</P>
<P>
Seventy-three delegates, including 52 from 13 foreign
countries, are participating in the seminar, the second of a
series of yearly workshops. The first workshop was held last year
in Jakarta, Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
