<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees in NE Kenya Receives Half Food Rations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) has
enough relief food stocks in Mombasa but has been forced to cut
food rations by half for refugees in northeastern Kenya because
of insufficient funds to airlift them.
</P>
<P>
WFP Country Director Mike Sackett was quoted as saying Sunday
that "15 day rations were cut in half for the first time at the
beginning of March when the road to the camps was impassable and
the funds for air transport insufficient."
</P>
<P>
The 50 percent cut in food rations for refugees in Kenya's
northeast would have to continue until the end of this month, the
U.N. official added.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the fleet of smaller food trucks currently
being used to move the food to the camps carries an average of 60
tons of food per day.
</P>
<P>
The roads leading to the refugee camps are currently
impassable as a result of heavy rains caused by the El Nino
phenomenon since last October.
</P>
<P>
For the three Dadaah camps, the WFP provides about 2,000 tons
of food each month to the 125,000 Somali refugees in Kenya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
