<HEADLINE> Cambodian Populism Party Moves into New Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Reastr Niyum (Populism) Party
is committed to national reconciliation and cooperation to create hope
and a prosperous future for all Cambodians, Ung Huot said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot, First Prime Minister and President of the Populism Party,
made the remarks at his keynote address delivered at the inauguration
of the party's new Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
He said, "we are committed to working for the benefit of the
people and the nation. We cannot stand by and let the turmoil
that has plagued Cambodia continue".
</P>
<P>
Ung Huot also expressed his party's supports to the Japanese
initiative in proposing a solution to the current crisis that
threatened to delay the electoral process.
</P>
<P>
The Populism Party was set up on February 1, 1998. The members of
the party are from the royalist FUNCINPEC party, which had been in
fragile after the July, 1997 event when its leader Prince Norodom
Ranariddh was ousted from power. Now the party was expected to has at
least ten thousand members.
</P>
<P>
More than two thousand people took part the inauguration, including
those who came from other provinces. Some diplomatic envoys to
Cambodia were also present. 
</P>
</TEXT>
