<HEADLINE> India Plans to Build Second Aircraft Carrier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- India is on the threshold of
building its second aircraft carrier, the Press Trust of India
reported Monday, quoting Vice Chief of Indian Naval Staff Sushil
Kumar.
</P>
<P>
Talking to reporters in Calcutta, capital of the eastern state
of West Bengal, Vice Admiral Kumar said the Cabinet Committee on
Security had already approved the plan and "all it required now
was the government's approval."
</P>
<P>
The Vice Admiral said the ship would be built at Cochin
Shipyard of the Southern Kerala State and the estimated cost would
be around 15 billion rupees (approximately 390 million U.S.
dollars), which would be invested over a span of 8 to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
India had two aircraft carriers, Viraat and Majestic, with the
Viraat retired from service in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Coast Guard Vice Admiral R. N. Ganesh said
the activities of the Indian Coast Guard were affected due to the
lack of sufficient vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
