<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's CPI for February Up 4.4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's consumer price
index (CPI) in February expanded by 4.4 percent to 114.3 compared
with the same period last year, according to figures released by
the Statistics Department Monday.
</P>
<P>
For the January-February period, the CPI, a measure of
inflation, increased by 3.8 percent from the same period in 1997,
the department said.
</P>
<P>
In comparison with the previous month, the CPI for February
1998 increased by 1.5 percent, it said.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the increase in the CPI for the first
two months of this year was brought about by increases in the
indices of all main groups, notably food which increased by 5.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
Other increases were miscellaneous goods and services (7.1
percent); medical care and health expenses (4.8 percent); gross
rent, fuel and power (4.5 percent).
</P>
<P>
A reclassification of items according to their durability and
services rendered showed increases in non-durable goods by 1.9
percent, services by 1.7 percent, semi-durable goods 0.9 percent
while the index for durable goods decreased by 0.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
