<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A further rise in News Corp.
shares and mining stocks balanced out a fall in telecommunications
giant Telstra installment receipts and other key stocks, leaving
the Australian sharemarket almost steady Monday.
</P>
<P>
The All Ordinaries Index closed 1.7 points lower at 2729.9 in
lower volumes as traders awaited leads from northern hemisphere
markets to emerge Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"It's a typical Monday trading market, largely unchanged, where
we wait for indications from the northern markets. There was
nothing out there that was a driving force," Bill Richmond from
Peake Lands Kirwan said.
</P>
<P>
The All Industrials Index fell 2.2 points to 4692.3.
</P>
<P>
News Corp. ordinary shares rose 18 cents to 10.09 Australian
dollars and the preferred shares 21 cents to 8.51 Australian
dollars after a further lift in the U.S. depositary receipts.
</P>
<P>
All eyes were on Telstra interim receipts Monday after Sunday's
announcement by Prime Minister John Howard that the government
would float off the remaining two-thirds of the telecommunications
company if returned at the next election.
</P>
<P>
The installment receipts fell by 7 cents to 3.78 Australian
dollars on a volume of 19.29 million.
</P>
<P>
Major banking stocks all declined, with ANZ's 23.5-cent drop to
10.075 Australian dollars being the most pronounced.
</P>
<P>
Westpac slid 3 cents to 10.48 Australian dollars, National
Australia Bank 15 cents to 20.9 dollars and Commonwealth 5 cents
t0 17.75 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The All Resources Index closed 1.5 points lower at 1162.6.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto shares fell 30.7 cents to 19.16 Australian dollars
after going ex-dividend, while BHP went up just half a cent to
15.655 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index dropped 1.5 points to 1106.8 as the bullion
price closed in Sydney at 294.05 U.S. dollars per ounce, down from
Friday's close of 294.8 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 288.68 million shares at a value of
536.19 million U.S. dollars, with falls outnumbering rises 597 to
475.  
</P>
</TEXT>
