<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Finance Minister Urges Continuous Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Outgoing Indian Finance
Minister P. Chidambaram called upon the next government to
continue the current economic reforms especially those in the
financial and public sectors.
</P>
<P>
"The way to a bright and prosperous future is to affirm
economic reforms and ensure that they gather pace," Chidambaram
said in a bowing-out statement released on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement dwelt on the current state of the Indian economy
and recounted the achievements of the 21-month-old United Front
government.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the statement appears to pre-empt any whole-sale
criticism by the new government of the way the United Front
government has managed the economy.
</P>
<P>
Indian President Kocheril Raman Narayanan Sunday evening
authorized Atal Behari Vajpayee, leader of the Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP), to form a new government, which is expected to take
oath Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The BJP-led coalition is planning to come out with a white
paper on the state of the economy, focusing on its weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
Among the major achievements of the United Front government,
Chidambaram listed the lowest inflation in 12 years of 5 percent
in 1997-98 and the "respectable" gross domestic product (GDP)
growth rate of 5 to 6 percent, though it is below the 7.5 percent
in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The debt service ratio is estimated at below 20 percent in the
financial year of 1997-98 compared to 24.3 percent in 1995-96 and
the debt to GDP ratio is estimated to have fallen to 24 percent in
1997-98 from 28.2 percent in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram claimed that the United Front government has
succeeded in adding 2 billion U.S. dollars to the country's
foreign exchange reserves in 1997-98 despite an increasingly
uncertain and hostile international economic environment.
</P>
<P>
He urged the new government not to forget the lessons learned
during the past seven years, saying a tight control on government
expenditure, limits on government borrowing and reduction of
fiscal deficit are necessary conditions for ensuring high growth,
low inflation and moderate indebtedness.
</P>
<P>
On the external front, the outgoing minister suggested that the
next government cope imaginatively with the new challenges posed
by the continuing East Asia crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
