<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Butterfly Trade Has Bright Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Experts point out that China
should attach great importance to the development of its butterfly
trade and enter the international market with related products.
</P>
<P>
International Business Daily recently carried an article
pointing to the bright prospects and great potential for the
nation's butterfly trade.
</P>
<P>
This Beijing-based newspaper said the annual worldwide trade
volume for butterfly products stands at several hundred million US
dollars, with Taiwan's annual exports of related products valued
at dozens of millions US dollars. The article noted that hundreds
of thousands people currently work in Taiwan's butterfly sector.
</P>
<P>
However, small-scale display centers in China's inland areas
currently offer nothing more than samples of butterflies used for
popular science, collecting and education purposes. Related
processing levels for butterfly products remain relatively low.
</P>
<P>
China is home to some 1,300 of the world's 14,000 butterfly
species, and thus is one of the richest countries in terms of
related resources
</P>
<P>
Collection has no affect on reproduction since butterflies die
soon after mating, according to experts. Therefore, protecting
their natural habitat will ensure the longevity of butterfly
resources.
</P>
<P>
Reports indicate that Chinese experts have recorded major
progress in research related to breeding, collecting and producing
samples, as well as establishing butterflies as a possible food
source. 
</P>
</TEXT>
