<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 09:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Protests Against Israeli Statement on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Jordanian official Sunday
summoned Israeli Ambassador to Jordan Odid Airan to protest
against statements on assassination of Hamas leader Khaled Mashaal
made by an Israeli cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
"Jordan rejects any assault on the life of any citizen whether
it was carried out inside or outside the kingdom and considers
(what Sharon said) a threat to its security and a violation of
international law," Jordan's official news agency quoted acting
Minister of Foreign Affairs Talal Sata'an Hassan as saying.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon has said that
the Israeli government was determined to kill Mashaal, who
survived the assassination attempt by two Israeli Mossad agents
last September in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Israel had informed Jordan that it intended "to finish off the
job" of assassinating Mashaal, but not on Jordanian soil, Sharon
has reportedly said.
</P>
<P>
"It is strange to issue such statements at a time when all the
parties concerned are seeking to bring the peace march back on
track in order to fulfill the peace that guarantees security and
stability in the Middle East," the Jordanian official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jordan's Deputy Prime Minister for Services and
Minister of Information Abdullah Nsour said that "Mashaal is a
Jordanian citizen protected by the Jordanian law and the
leadership of Jordan and we will never accept such threats to his
life."
</P>
<P>
"The statements do not tally with statements made by the
Israeli government earlier that it was willing to regain
understanding with the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We denounce these statements. The Ministry of Foreign Affairs
will take the appropriate action," Nsour said in a statement to
the news agency.
</P>
<P>
Also joining the protests were Speaker of the Lower House of
Parliament Saad Hail El Sorour and Abdullah El-Jazi, head of the
Arab and International Affairs Committee of the Jordanian
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
Such statements violated Jordanian security and contradicted
with the Jordanian-Israeli peace treaty signed in 1994, El-Jazi
told Jordan's official news agency.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Hamas (anti-Israeli Islamic Resistance Movement)
warned Israel that it would retaliate if the Jewish state carried
out the threat.
</P>
<P>
"The Zionists' attempts to whitewash the image of its secret
security service (Mossad) will not pass unpunished. The time
when their crimes were carried out without punishment has
vanished," said a statement issued by Hamas' office in Amman.
</P>
<P>
Two Israeli Mossad agents holding fake Canadian passports were
arrested after they attempted to kill Mashaal in Amman on
September 23 last year, and later released in exchange for the
release of Hamas founder Sheikh Ahmed Yassin.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian-Israeli relations sharply deteriorated over the
assassination attempt. Mossad chief Danny Yatom resigned last
month after a series of failed operations.
</P>
<P>
The bilateral ties began to warm up as both sides exchanged
high-level visits and signed some agreements to boost bilateral
trade last week.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is the second Arab country after Egypt that signed peace
treaty with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
