<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Promotes Sino-South African Trade Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Developing trade ties with South
Africa in an active and orderly manner is not only of great
political significance, but also serves the needs of China's
multipolar marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
Liu Shanzai, China's vice-minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation, made the remarks during last week's Beijing
meeting on Sino-South African economic and trade policies and
investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, a major trade power in Africa and China's major
trade partner on the continent, enjoys an annual foreign trade
volume of 60 billion US dollars. The two nations also enjoy highly
complementary economies.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between China, including the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, and South Africa hit two billion US dollars
in 1997, and jumped to 2.55 billion US dollars in 1997. China
currently ranks as South Africa's fifth largest trade partner,
according to statistics released by the South African Ministry of
Trade and Industry.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of diplomatic relations on January 1, 1998,
has greatly promoted favorable conditions for economic and trade
contacts between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Liu stressed that efforts to expand and develop economic and
trade ties with South Africa should be implemented in an active
and orderly manner.
</P>
<P>
China should proceed with a full understanding of the situation
in South Africa, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Chinese enterprises are greatly attracted by the coexistence of
both first and third world consumption levels in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the nation enjoys the most advanced infrastructure
construction sector in Africa, and is considered to be the
bridgehead for exploring markets in the southern part of the
continent.
</P>
<P>
The most important factors Chinese enterprises hoping to
develop traded ties must remember is to gain a keen awareness of
the economic situation, market environment and investment demand
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Liu stressed that priority should be placed on establishing
enterprises and encouraging larger enterprises to participate in
major projects. He also expressed hope for doubling the originally
targeted bilateral trade volume for 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Children Suffer Malnutrition: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A quarter of all South
African children aged between six months and six years suffer
from malnutrition, the Star, a daily paper published here Monday
quoted experts as saying.
</P>
<P>
About 22.9 percent of children in South Africa are stunted, a
major symptom of malnutrition. Another 5.5 percent show other
symptoms of malnutrition, such as abnormally low weight,
according to a survey by the Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
Medical experts said malnutrition could cause serious mental
and physical problems for affected children.
</P>
<P>
"Without adequate food, young bodies and brains can't grow and
develop properly, these children will be stunted physically and
mentally, for the rest of their lives," said Jeanette Molefe of
the African Children's Feeding Scheme.
</P>
<P>
A study by a university-based research group, the South
African Vitamin A Consultative Group has shown that the highest
incidence of malnutrition is in the Northern Cape Province, with
the lowest being reported in KwaZulu Natal Province,
</P>
<P>
The study also found that the prevalence of malnutrition is
far higher in urban areas than in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
According to United Nations Children's Fund (Unicef), more
than 200 million children in developing countries under the age
of five are malnourished.
</P>
<P>
Malnutrition is responsible for more than half of all children
deaths worldwide, resulting in the death of at least six million
children under the age of five every year.
</P>
<P>
Prompted by the Unicef's decision to make malnutrition its
theme for the year, South Afirca's local and provincial
authorities have decided to address the problem.
</P>
<P>
Provincial and local authorities, non-government organizations
and the metro council will jointly focus on projects which will
include short and medium-term projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
