<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops Water-Saving Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China should develop water-saving
agriculture in view of the country's water shortages, stressed Niu
Maosheng, minister of water resources, recently.
</P>
<P>
Niu said that China should energetically spread water-saving
techniques in developing agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Using traditional irrigation methods such as allowing
water to flood fields rather than sinking, dripping or spraying
water onto the roots of crops, China's agriculture is very
wasteful to the already scarce water resources, Niu said.
</P>
<P>
With per-capita water resources of 2,300 cubic meters, roughly
a quarter of the world average, China is one of the 13
water-deficient countries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of February, 3.96 million hectares of farmland has
been affected by drought in northern China, while the south was
frequently threated by floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
