<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Sell 2 Largest Copper Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Zambia will finalize the sale
of two of its biggest copper mines by the end of this month,
Zambia Daily Mail reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper quoted Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM)
Privatization Chairman Francis Kaunda as saying here Sunday the
Kafue Consortium has offered 400 million U.S. Dollars for the
purchase and development of the Nkana and Nchanga mines and that
the deal is expected to be signed by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
He said a legal framework should be worked out and agreed on
so that neither party will renegade on the deal.
</P>
<P>
"The consortium was offered last year the purchase of the
package which include the two mines, now we have to sign those
agreements which were in general terms then," he said.
</P>
<P>
He explained that there is need to ensure that the consortium
which has offered to buy the package of Nkana and Nchanga mines
are bound by legal instruments so that what they promised to do
is attained.
</P>
<P>
"We have to make sure that what is in the agreement of offer
should be followed even after the deal has been concluded so that
we do not run into unnecessary problems in future, and this
process normally takes about three months," he said.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of the country's two largest mines is
expected to bring in huge sums of foreign exchange which would in
turn spiral economic activity on the Copperbelt.
</P>
<P>
The Kafue Consortium groups world mining houses such as Anglo
Vaal, Phelpe Dodge and the Commonwealth Development Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The privatization of the copper mines is part of the
government policy to liberalize the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
