<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Presidium Holds Fifth Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Presidium of the ongoing
First Session of the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC),
China's top legislature, in session here since early March, held
its fifth meeting this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was presided over by Li Peng, an executive chairman
of the Presidium and newly-elected chairman of the Ninth NPC
Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The meeting approved draft resolutions on work reports by the
NPC Standing Committee, the Supreme People's Court and the Supreme
People's Procuratorate. All three draft resolutions will be
printed and distributed to delegations to the current NPC session
for examination, and then be submitted to an NPC plenary meeting
for final approval.
</P>
<P>
The Presidium meeting also approved a report by the session's
secretariat on its suggestions for handling the motions submitted
by the deputies. The report was delivered by Cao Zhi, deputy
secretary-general of the current session.
</P>
<P>
Cao said that the session has received a total of 830 motions,
26 of which have been put forth by NPC delegations and the other
804 jointly submitted by more than 30 individual deputies each.
</P>
<P>
He said that after consultations with relevant departments, the
secretariat of the session suggests that 190 motions be handed
over to relevant NPC special committees for examination.
</P>
<P>
The special committees will suggest whether or not these
motions should be included in the agenda of an NPC session or an
NPC Standing Committee meeting, and the NPC Standing Committee
will make final decisions after further examination, he noted.
</P>
<P>
The other 640 motions, he said, will be forwarded to relevant
departments and organizations as suggestions, criticisms or ideas
by the General Office of the NPC Standing Committee, which is
responsible for informing deputies of the way their motions are
handled by relevant departments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
