<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Abuse Rampant in Kenya's Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- An anti-drug official has said
drugs were commonly abused by students in Kenyan secondary
schools and colleges, urging the government to fight against the
user, the supplier and the source of drugs.
</P>
<P>
Daily Nation Monday quoted Maina Wanbugu, Chairman of the
Anti-Dangerous Drugs Organization of kenya, as saying that about
10 percent of male students in Central Province were regular drug
users.
</P>
<P>
According to a study carried out in the province by the
organization, from a sample of 1,500 boys, 10 percent said that
they chew khat occasionally.
</P>
<P>
The drugs most commonly abused by students are bhang, alcohol,
and khat, and amphetanines are also commonly abused by female
students.
</P>
<P>
The study said that sources of the drugs include bars, drug
stores, auxiliary staff, social gatherings, shops and black
markets.
</P>
<P>
Wambugu attributed the rampant drug-abuse among students in
this East African country to peer influence and more pocket money
given by their parents. He recommended a concerted fight against
legalized advertisements of common used drugs in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
