<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS, S. Africa's Worst Enemy: Health Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 16 (Xinhua) -- South African Health
Minister Nkosazana Zuma has described AIDS/HIV as a bigger enemy
than apartheid in the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing medical students at the University of Transkei at
the weekend, Zuma said, "it (AIDS) knows no color, no race and no
class."
</P>
<P>
She said even if the government and South Africans went all
out to boost economic growth, all efforts would be in vain if the
HIV/AIDS pandemic were not taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said every day 1,500 South Africans became infected with
the disease. To date 2.8 million South Africans have the virus.
The bulk of those infected were between the ages of 15 and 40.
</P>
<P>
AIDS could, if left unattended, undermine efforts to build
South Africa, Zuma warned, adding that a World Bank study has
predicted South Africa would loose one percent of its gross
domestic products because of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The spread of AIDS would lead to high levels of absenteeism,
premature deaths of skilled and unskilled workers. Hundreds of
orphans left by young people who died of AIDS would create
enormous strain on the welfare services and the country's budget,
social expert predicted.
</P>
<P>
The South African government reportedly has taken over the
AIDS/HIV campaign from the Department of Health. A cabinet
sub-committee, chaired by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, has been
established to spearhead the campaign against AIDS. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
