<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fisheries Booming in Dry-Land Gansu Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- In the past, local people in
Gansu, a dry-land province in northwest China, had no idea that
one day they would have so much locally produced aquatic food on
their table.
</P>
<P>
However, the fishery industry has drawn a growing number of
local people into the lucrative business because of the
2-decades-old, market-led economic reform. Local aquatic products
also have been exported to European countries.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1997, the province turned out 93.15 million tons
of aquatic products, 201 times the figure in 1978 from local
rivers, including parts of the country's two largest -- the
Yangtze and the Yellow.
</P>
<P>
Gansu has enough sunshine for fish to grow, but for a long time
local production of aquatic food was very small. The saltwater
Qinghai Lake in neighboring Qinghai Province used to be the main
source of fish for Gansu.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, local governments in areas along the rivers
have encouraged people to develop freshwater fisheries with
financial and technological assistance.
</P>
<P>
So far, local authorities have held 52 training courses to help
local people and a series of local laws have been passed to ensure
smooth development of local fisheries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
