<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 08:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Cabinet Resigns Over Dispute With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, March 16 (Xinhua) -- All 15 Cabinet ministers in
Kuwait headed by Crown Prince and Prime Minister Sheikh Saad
Al-Abdullah Al-Salem Al-Sabah resigned Sunday night over a dispute
with parliament.
</P>
<P>
The resignation was accepted by Kuwait Emir Sheikh Jaber
Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah, local newspapers reported Monday, quoting
sources close to the emir as saying that an emiri decree in this
regard would be issued, but ruled out the dissolution of the
National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet resignation has been seen as a government attempt
to abort a vote of no-confidence against Information Minister
Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah, who was accused of violating the
country's laws through allowing controversial books to be publicly
displayed.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait saw the most serious clash between the National Assembly
and government last Tuesday on grilling the information minister
as the crown prince and prime minister strongly criticized some
parliamentary members of trying to abuse democracy in Kuwait,
which is the only Gulf state that has a parliament.
</P>
<P>
A total of 10 Islamic members in the parliament submitted a
motion on March 10 for a vote of no-confidence against the
information minister.
</P>
<P>
According to Kuwaiti constitution, a no-confidence will be
taken up for voting on Tuesday, seven days following it was tabled
in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
A non-confidence motion needs a simple majority to pass in the
50-member parliament. Four Kuwaiti cabinet ministers who are also
parliamentary members are not allowed to vote and, therefore, 24
votes for the motion will let the minister out.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentary members supporting the vote have spent the last
few days frantically lobbying more back-up from their fellow
members and sources were quoted as saying that as many as 30
members were ready to vote the minister out of office.
</P>
<P>
Political sources said Sheikh Saad had discussed the issue
with some presenters of the no-confidence motion who refused to
withdraw it.
</P>
<P>
Members of the Cabinet submitted their resignations to Crown
Prince Sheikh Saad to show solidarity with the information
minister and relieve Sheikh Saad of embarrassment with regard to
the current crisis. Sheikh Saad had conveyed the resignations to
Emir Sheikh Jaber Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah earlier Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister sternly warned the opposition political
group last Tuesday that their activities could put the country's
future at stake, explaining that his government would not be
lenient with those who were trying to undermine the country's
security.
</P>
<P>
The motion against Sheikh Saud is the fourth such motion in
Kuwait's 35 years of democracy, but none of the three previous
no-confidence attempts had passed.
</P>
<P>
One parliamentary member was quoted as saying that the
government decision not to go to parliament Tuesday for the
no-confidence vote move means that it realizes that it does not
have enough votes to save the minister.
</P>
<P>
The current cabinet, which includes 15 ministers, four of whom
are elected members of parliament, was formed in October, 1996
after general elections.
</P>
<P>
Political observers here expect Sheikh Saad to conduct a
cabinet reshuffle in the next few days which could bring back
Sheikh Saud in another ministry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
