<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Leaves 30 Dar Residents Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Thirty people in Dar es
Salaam have been made homeless after a fire gutted two flats on
Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
Properties worth thousands of Dollars were destroyed by the
fire in the first flat, leaving six families in despair. The
second flat was also razed to the ground, Daily News reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
But owner of the house Mohammed Dikata claimed some people who
came to the rescue had stolen three mattresses, three radios,
chairs and clothes.
</P>
<P>
The "good Samaritans" threw most of the valuables out to safe
places. They had even opened three big holes on the walls to pull
out belongings, Dikata told the paper.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Dakita claimed he lost 500,000 shillings (about
740 U.S. Dollars) of cash while his young brother lost 800,000
shillings in chaos.
</P>
<P>
The Dar es Salaam Regional Police Commander, Alfred Gewe,
confirmed the incident, saying the police were still trying to
establish the cause of the fire.
</P>
<P>
One of the six tenants in the first flat at Bunguruni-Pandia,
Aziza Ali, aged 35, said the house caught fire at 8:30 pm and
continued till the early hours of the next day. Fire is believed
to spread from the first flat to the second in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
She said the fire started burning from the ceiling of her
bedroom. "I entered my bedroom at 8:30 pm and found the room full
of smoke as the fire razed the ceiling board made of carton box
pieces."
</P>
<P>
Ali said she tried to put out the fire with water but in vain.
</P>
<P>
The woman said it is difficult for her to know the cause of
the fire which destroyed everything of her family except the
clothes they have on. The house had no electric power.
</P>
<P>
Her neighbor phoned the police and City Commission Fire
Brigade Unit which arrived at the scene at 10 p.m. and managed to
extinguish the fire.
</P>
<P>
The homeless people have appealed for relief of temporary
shelter and food. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
