<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Bulk Handling Facility to Be Built in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A giant bulk handling facility
at the port of Mombasa to be ready by March next year is expected
to significantly reduce congestion at the port, The East African
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The modern bulk grain and fertilizer handling facility to be
built at a cost of 32 million U.S. Dollars would greatly improve
ship turn-around at the port by almost 75 percent, the weekly
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Assistant Minister for Finance Mathias Keah was quoted
as saying last week that the project was the biggest single
capital investment venture in sub-Saharan Africa recently.
</P>
<P>
Once complete, the new facility will enable vessels to be
discharged by two Buhler Protalino mechanical ship unloaders with
a design capacity of 14,000 tons per day.
</P>
<P>
The bulk commodities will be transferred from the port to the
transit handling facility by two 600-ton-per-day conveyor
systems, one for cereals and the other for fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
The facility will be made of steel silos with an initial
capacity for 67,200 tons of cereals and a flat storage area for
18,000 tons of fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the bulk commodity handling facility
is the first of its kind between the Suez Canal and Cape of Good
Hope. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
