<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight Farmers Become Civil Servants in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Eight farmers in Guangyuan city
in southwest China's Sichuan Province, have been appointed as
leading officials in the township governments this year because
of their outstanding capability in handling governmental affairs.
</P>
<P>
The farmers were selected by the local personnel bureau after
they had gone through strict procedures which included a written
test, interview and physical examination.
</P>
<P>
As an experiment to recruit civil servants, the Guangyuan
personnel bureau conducted open examinations for 170 village
officials recently. Those who served as village leaders for more
than three years could take the exam to compete for township
government positions.
</P>
<P>
Township government officials said the farmer-civil servants
should be able to do their new jobs well because they were born in
rural areas and are familiar with the conditions.
</P>
<P>
The system of recruiting civil servants through open exams
is also practiced in China's central and provincial government
departments.
</P>
<P>
Governments at the provincial, county and township levels in 18
provinces even held unified exams to recruit new officials. A
total of 520,000 people competed for the 53,000 offered
positions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
