<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Sends Troops to Zambian-Angolan Border </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has sent over 500 soldiers
to its borders with Angola, the most influential and leading
independent newspaper, the Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted military sources who confirmed the movement
as saying Sunday that the troops traveling in eight 75 seater
buses are moved to the country's North Western province to
increase the one company's combat strength initially deployed
there.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's military buildup in border areas comes two weeks
after Angola warned Zambia of possible military aggression if
supplies of arms from its territory to the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) forces is not stopped.
</P>
<P>
The increased deployment of troops by Zambia army's 4th
battalion (4ZR) of the infantry unit appears to be in response to
the charges made by Manuel Augusto, Angolan Ambassador to Zambia
that arms have been transported through Zambia to the UNITA,
which was denied by the Zambian government.
</P>
<P>
But there are speculations among diplomats here that Zambia's
military buildup can be a relief measure to curb the alleged arms
supplies to the UNITA and possible aggression.
</P>
<P>
In a news briefing held in Lusaka on March 5, Augusto told
Zambia to take "appropriate" measures to control the gun-running
racket and if failed to do it the Angolan government "would have
no option but to defend it's citizens who have been dying in
large numbers in the past few years."
</P>
<P>
The Angolan ambassador warned that while Angola does not wish
to have a repeat of the Congo (B) and Congo (K) incidents where
his government participated in dislodging the governments there.
</P>
<P>
"Angola does not rule out any option if UNITA did not stop
getting arms from some territories," said Augusto, adding his
government is aware that the rebel organization is using a
certain "neighbor" to supply arms to its strongholds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
