<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong Province Helps Guangxi Shake Off Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- This capital city of south
China's Guangdong Province donated more than 30 million yuan in
1997 to help resettle 2,000 impoverished households in Bose
Prefecture in southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Guangzhou has aided the prefecture in
developing its natural resources and improving the construction of
basic facilities by absorbing overseas investment, holding trade
fairs and training local officials.
</P>
<P>
As a result, three resettled villages, with a population of
more than 10,000 farmers, harvested 3.24 million kilograms of
grain in 1997. The per-capita grain and net income reached
320 kilograms and 850 yuan, respectively.
</P>
<P>
With the aid of Guangzhou, these villages spruced up their
infrastructure with 238-kilometers of highways and 10 schools
covering 3,960 square meters. So far, more than 4,800 villagers
have access to electricity and clean water, said an official from
the regional government.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that Bose, located on the banks of the scenic
Chengbi Lake, is home to a variety of ethnic minority groups, such
as the Zhuang, Yao Miao and Yi. The prefecture is best-known as
the site of a Red Army uprising led by Deng Xiaoping in December
of 1929.
</P>
<P>
In the future, Guangzhou will pay more attention to helping the
villagers get training and grasp agricultural production
techniques, said Chen Kaizhi, vice-mayor of the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
