<HEADLINE> Egypt's Sandstorm Delays Cook's Mideast Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A sandstorm engulfing Cairo for 24
hours has forced British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook's plane to
land in Cyprus on his way to Egypt, Egyptian Presidential Palace
officials said Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Cook was scheduled to arrive here Sunday night at the first leg
of his first-ever mission to the Middle East to unblock the
deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He was supposed to meet Monday morning with President Hosni
Mubarak and then with other government officials.
</P>
<P>
But the seasonal sandstorm has had his trip postponed to a
later hour when the dust wind subsides, according to an
information officer in the Itihadiya Palace, where talks between
Mubarak and Cook will take place.
</P>
<P>
The sandstorm hit Cairo Sunday morning, raising temperature by
11 degrees centigrade, turning the sky into a yellow blanket, and
reducing visibility to about 500 meters, according to Director
of the Egyptian Metereological Center Mohammed Abudulla Ahman
Mahran.
</P>
<P>
Poor visibility has forced several incoming flights in Cairo
diverted to eastern and southern Egypt as strong gust halted
operation of transit ships and ferry boats in the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
Khamaseen, meaning in Arabic 50-day wind, usually sweeps across
Egypt in spring, packing desert sand into the cities and towns
in the Nile Valley.
</P>
<P>
Weathermen expect temperatures to drop by 16 degrees Monday,
accompanied by rain and even hailstorm in some areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
