<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Releases Agricultural White Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's agricultural unions
have produced a white paper outlining measures that need to be
undertaken to boost export earnings and increase overall crop and
livestock production.
</P>
<P>
The 21-page document, "Agriculture in Zimbabwe 1998" released
here Sunday, was compiled by the Zimbabwean Farmers' Union, the
Commercial Farmers' Union and the Indigenous Commercial Farmers'
Union and looks at the contribution of selected crops to the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The document noted that while focus should be placed on
increasing the total crop and livestock production, water storage
and development played the most important role in the
agricultural industry.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the paper recommended that to increase
productivity in the small-scale sector and to ensure food
security in drought times, it was imperative that the potential
for irrigation was developed.
</P>
<P>
About 40 percent of Zimbabwe's export earnings are derived
from agriculture in raw or semi-processed form.
</P>
<P>
The main export earners are tobacco, horticulture, cotton
lint, sugar, beef, coffee, maize and poultry products.
</P>
<P>
On tobacco, the document noted while Zimbabwe was the second
largest exporter after Brazil, exporting 98 percent of its
overall production and with about 21 percent of world trade,
there was need to improve the 21 percent world market share with
good quality tobacco.
</P>
<P>
This could be achieved by maintaining the large-scale
commercial sub-sector efficiencies, expanding production in the
small-scale sub-sector through the expansion of tobacco schemes,
keeping costs down without compromising quality and improving the
quality of support services.
</P>
<P>
The horticultural industry has experienced phenomenal growth
and is now the third largest in terms of value of output in
commercial agriculture.
</P>
<P>
But due to substantial growth in producing countries, there
was now a worldwide over-production of some flowers like roses.
</P>
<P>
The document made it quite clear that the liberalization of
maize marketing in the country had made information on
production, marketing and pricing more difficult and this tended
to affect farmers' plans and government's policy.
</P>
<P>
The paper recommended that crop forecasting systems and
methods need to be improved.
</P>
<P>
One of the main recommendations on maize was that the
strategic grain reserve needed to take the livestock industry
requirements into account to prevent fluctuations in livestock
output caused by periods of high maize prices due to drought or
shortages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
