<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> University Vice-President on Juvenile Class </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese University of Science
and Technology (CUST), a cradle of juvenile class in China, will
go on enrolling young prodigies at its juvenile class this year.
</P>
<P>
Zheng Yongfei, vice-president of the CUST, which is located in
east China's Anhui Province, made the remark at the Ninth National
People's Congress in session here since early March.
</P>
<P>
The university has recruited approximately 1,000 prodigies
since its founding of a juvenile class in 1978, with an average
recruitment of 50 each year with the youngest aged only nine.
</P>
<P>
To date, about one third of the prodigy graduates have gone
overseas for advanced studies and some are working in cooperation
with scientists of other countries, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
As most of these young talents have been wise since childhood
and fast in learning things new, they usually complete the junior
or even senior middle school courses when they are pupils at
primary schools, he said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with other college students, those at juvenile classes
are doing much better with the subjects to their own interest than
other students. Nevertheless, a few are easily upset because of a
somewhat weak character resultant from meticulous care of their
parents. And a small number of these youngsters had to suspend
their studies for their failure to adapt themselves to changes in
life on the campus, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
To cope with this, the university should pay attention to their
interests as well as to their study in the basic theories, so as to
enable them to develop morally, intellectually and physically, he
urged.
</P>
<P>
So far, juvenile classes have also been set up in a number of
other universities despite the differing views on whether it is
good or not to run such classes, Zheng said.
</P>
<P>
But he pledged that the CUST would continue running the
juvenile classes as it is an essential exploration in the field of
education in a country with a population of 1.2 billion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
