<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increased Input Shows China's Commitment to Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- China is fully committed to
environmental protection, according to a top Chinese environmental
official.
</P>
<P>
"This determination is fully demonstrated in the government
work report delivered by Li Peng at this year's session of the
National People's Congress (NPC)," said Qu Geping, director of the
NPC Resources and Environment Subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
"For the first time, environmental protection is listed as a
government investment priority, on a par with agriculture,
forestry, water conservation, energy, transport and telecoms," Qu
said.
</P>
<P>
Annual government funding for environmental protection
undertakings has exceeded 50 billion yuan in the last five years.
And nearly 70,000 polluting enterprises across the country have
been shut down during the last three years,"a move rarely seen in
any parts of the world," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
The clean-up of the Huihe, one of the most polluted rivers in
the country, unveiled in 1994, cost central and local governments
some 5 billion yuan from 1994-97, and another 15 billion yuan will
be spent continuing the clean-up before the year 2000, according
to Qu, one of the founders of China's green movement.
</P>
<P>
China's five-year plan covering the 1996-2000 period projects a
total investment of 450 billion yuan for environmental protection
projects across the country, or 0.8 percent of the country's GDP.
"As a matter of fact, annual input in a dozen coast cities has
exceeded that percentage," Qu said.
</P>
<P>
However, the tasks ahead are more difficult to accomplish, with
problems ranging from severe and almost nationwide water shortages
to soil erosion and a continuous shrinkage of farm land, said the
environment official.
</P>
<P>
He said that, despite the country's intensive efforts, water
and air pollution is still rampant. Each of the seven main rivers
in the country has had half of its length polluted and, of the
600-strong cities nationwide, only five or six enjoy clean air
defined as first-grade by the state.
</P>
<P>
China has promulgated 15 laws and regulations on protection of
natural resources and the environment. "The most important thing
to do now is to strengthen law enforcement," Qu stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 More Zimbabwean Sites Named in World Heritage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Matopo Hills, south of Zimbabwe's
second largest city Bulawayo, and the Ziwa settlements in east
Zimbabwe were Sunday nominated for listing among the world's most
endangered sites, the Zimbabwe News Agency Ziana reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Museums and Monuments of Zimbabwe (NMMZ) and
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization
(UNESCO)'s World Heritage Committee said the two sites should be
put on the world heritage list.
</P>
<P>
UNESCO's Southern and Central African Representative Lupwishi
Mbuyamba Sunday said in Bulawayo that once on the world's most
endangered list the sites would benefit from a world heritage
fund.
</P>
<P>
"The fund was set up to assist in the preservation of such
sites and their promotion as historical and cultural sites that
society can learn from and appreciate," said Mbuyamba.
</P>
<P>
NMMZ Executive Director and World Heritage Committee member
Dawson Munjeri said Matopo Hills where the founder of Rhodesia,
Cecil John Rhodes, was buried along with several Ndebele chiefs
were of significant historical and cultural value to Zimbabwe and
the world.
</P>
<P>
The Ziwa settlements, ruins of pre-colonial Manyika settlers
north of Nyanga in Manicaland province's eastern highlands were
also noted.
</P>
<P>
If put on the world heritage list, the two sites would join great
Zimbabwe in Masvingo of South Zimbabwe and Khami ruins west of
Bulawayo, two Shona settlements of the 15th century that have been
preserved as cultural sites. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
