<HEADLINE> Australia Urged to Become Model for Electronic Commerce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia was urged Monday by
Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates in Sydney to capitalize on the
growing popularity of the Internet by becoming a model for
electronic commerce and publishing.
</P>
<P>
Gates, who founded Microsoft two decades ago and whose
operating system is now installed on over 90 percent of the
world's personal computers, said politicians world-wide had
already recognized the importance of the Internet to the
competitiveness of their countries in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
"In the infrastructure that exists here with the skills, the
use of English, there are some incredible opportunities for
Australia in particular," he was quoted by the Australian
Associated Press as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gates, who has a personal fortune estimated at 37 billion US
dollars, is on a two-day whirlwind visit to Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It's an incredible opportunity to share government
information, to improve the educational system, to allow the
businesses in the country to reach out in a way they never did
before."
</P>
<P>
Gates spent an hour at a media conference in Sydney about his
vision for information technology which he said was still at the
"Paleolithic stage" of development.
</P>
<P>
"Basically we're at the early age," Gates said.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe in 10 years from now we'll be through the early stages
of the Information Age."
</P>
<P>
With the evolution of the Internet, governments faced major
challenges including addressing privacy concerns and accessibility
to technology for the entire population, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
