<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oceanologist on Developing Marine Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Though he has recently received
surgery, Zeng Chengkui, the oldest deputy to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, in session here
since early March, looks energetic and talks with a clear mind.
</P>
<P>
As one of the country's leading oceanologists, Zeng, 88, has
served as an NPC deputy for seven consecutive terms since 1964.
</P>
<P>
"In my 30-plus-year career as a people's deputy, I have put
forth a lot of motions and suggestions, most of which urge the
state to attach importance to science and technology," says Zeng,
who is an academician of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
He notes that development of science and technology is a
basic guarantee for any country's economic growth and social
progress, especially for a relatively backward country like China.
</P>
<P>
As an oceanologist who has devoted his life to marine study,
Zeng says that he and some other deputies have put forward a joint
proposal to the current NPC session, urging intensified efforts in
developing "marine agriculture", or the breeding of aquatic
products in marine water.
</P>
<P>
"For a populous country like China, it is of vital importance
to develop sea-water breeding and turn the ocean into a major food
supplier," he notes.
</P>
<P>
In the 1950s, Zeng headed a research group of the Marine
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, which solved major
technical problems in the breeding of kelp and helped raise
China's annual kelp output to 600,000 tons, the world's highest.
</P>
<P>
Despite his senior age, Zeng is still engaged in research on
marine alga and seaweeds. Thanks to efforts by Zeng and other
local marine scientists, Shandong, a coastal province in east
China which is Zeng's hometown, has enjoyed the country's most
developed marine economy.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the output value of Shandong's marine economy
exceeded 80 billion yuan (about 10 billion US dollars), one third
of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
China has paid increasing attention to marine science and
technology in recent years. The central government has decided to
spend one billion yuan on marine science in the five-year period
from 1996 to 2000, 10 times more than in the previous five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Bank Opens, Aiming at Assets of Closed Firms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A newly-established bank,
Radhanasin Bank, officially opened Monday, which plans to bid for
good assets of the 56 finance companies that were closed last
December.
</P>
<P>
Radhanasin Bank, Thailand's 16th bank and the sixth state-run
institution, will be headed by former Bangkok Bank president
Vichit Surapongchai and has an initial capital base of four
billion baht (100 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The bank, seen as the realization of the government's "good
bank" concept, was established by the government last year, along
with the Asset Management Corporation, which will take on the
financial sector assets no one else wants to buy.
</P>
<P>
It is believed to be part of the government's efforts to
alleviate Thailand's banking problems and to bring stability,
confidence and trust back to the Thai financial system.
</P>
<P>
Some of the non-core assets of the 56 closed firms, such as
cars and antiques, had been auctioned last month by the Financial
Restructuring Authorities.
</P>
<P>
But the core assets, such as loans and bond holdings, are still
waiting for marketing.
</P>
<P>
Local financial institutions reportedly carry 1.3 trillion baht
(32.5 billion dollars) in non-performing and poorly-performing
loans, equal to about a quarter of the total credit system.
</P>
<P>
Radhanasin Bank will compete with local and foreign
institutions in an open bidding process to buy the assets of the
closed firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
