<HEADLINE> EA Countries to Hold Joint Military Exercises in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda are
scheduled to hold joint military exercises in Kenya this June in
a bid to enhance regional military cooperation, the East African
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper quoted Kenya's Department of Defense as
saying that each of the three east African countries would be
free to send whatever detachments it could afford to take part in
the show.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan People's Defense Forces public relations officer,
Captain Shaban Batarinza, told the paper that the exercise is
designed to promote east African military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
If need arose, he added, the forces of the three countries
could be used for peace-keeping operations.
</P>
<P>
The joint exercises are being seen in Uganda as the first step
toward the formation of the United States-mooted standing
regional peace-keeping force, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that America had been encouraging closer
military cooperation in the east African region in order to form
a joint force to carry out peace-keeping and humanitarian
missions.
</P>
<P>
Last month, defense chiefs of the three east African countries
met in Nairobi to discuss security and defense cooperation
following a similar meeting held last November in Arusha,
Northern Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the United States organized a training course on
defense resource management for Kenyan military officers in
Nairobi and similar arrangements are in place for Uganda and
Tanzania. 
</P>
</TEXT>
