<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Seeks Closer Ties With Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, March 16 (Xinhua) -- North China's Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region plans to promote economic and trade cooperation
with Hong Kong in order to make full use of the latter's unique
advantages.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a recent meeting on the region's opening effort,
Wang Fengqi, vice chairman of the autonomous region, said that
Hong Kong's return to China on July 1, 1997, has not only created
favorable conditions which will enable the new administrative
region to play a greater role in linking interior areas with the
international economy, but also offers bright prospects for closer
cooperation between the two regions.
</P>
<P>
Wang expressed hope for multi-dimensional forms of cooperation
and pledged that Inner Mongolia will strictly observe the
principle of mutual benefit and basing cooperation on
complementary advantages.
</P>
<P>
He said Inner Mongolia will issue more stocks and bonds in Hong
Kong in order to attract more foreign funds to develop
wide-ranging sectors, including agriculture, animal husbandry,
energy and environmental protection. He added that the region will
extend great efforts and with Hong Kong's help to attract more
representative offices of overseas banking and financial
organizations in the region.
</P>
<P>
Wang also noted that efforts will be made to increase exports
of manufactured commodities and to promote the introduction of
advanced foreign techniques.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia has entrusted exclusive business rights to a
local Hong Kong company and invited two businessmen from Hong Kong
to serve as senior economic advisors.
</P>
<P>
Inner Mongolia, which covers 1.18 million sq.km. and is home to
120 varieties of mineral resources, is one of China's five leading
pastoral regions.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-nine Hong Kong companies registered business operations
in Inner Mongolia during 1997, with total investments standing at
well over 45 million U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
