<HEADLINE> India, Russia Discuss Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Concerned over a decline in
bilateral trade, India is discussing a composite long-term trade
agreement with Russia, a leading Indian newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting official sources, the Hindustan Times said the pact
would be signed when Russian President Boris Yeltsin visits India
later this year.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by the Indian side, bilateral
turnover between the two countries declined from 63.6 billion
rupees (approximately 1.93 billion US dollars) in 1995-96 to 49.95
billion rupees (approximately 1.33 billion US dollars) in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
India hopes that the pact would weed out the existing anomalies
that have crept into the rupee trade mechanism, and boost economic
and trade cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are keen to sort out outstanding issues like the
long-pending plan to set up a State Bank of India (SBI) subsidiary
in Moscow, the capital of Russia.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the Russian commitment to set up a representative
office of Incombank in India was yet to materialize even though
the Reserve Bank of India has already provided the necessary
clearances.
</P>
<P>
The Hindustan Times said that the problems faced by trading
communities of both countries were discussed on several occasions
but emphasis was lacking.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have also discussed the establishment of proper
shipping channels to spur bilateral trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka City Population Exceeds Capacity: Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The capital city of Bangladesh is
good for 3 million people, but about 9 million are living in the
metropolis straining its services, Mayor Mohammad Hanif said.
</P>
<P>
Hanif was speaking at a three-day workshop on Sunday on Dhaka
City Management Reform, part of a participatory process in
developing a plan for reforming the administration and improving
the services in the city, press reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
To some, the city covering an area of 365 square kilometers was
full of problems, and to many others, it was one of unlimited
opportunities, he said.
</P>
<P>
Most of those came to the city with great hopes to earn a
living, and they ultimately ended up as beggars, hawkers and
richshaw pullers, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He made a call to decentralize development activities to stop
the migration of people to the city from rural areas for a
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
Fifty percent of the residents in the city were poor, with the
rest belonging to the middle- and high-income brackets, according
to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by the Bangladesh Center for Advanced
Studies and other institutions, was opened on Sunday and attended
by participants from India, Sri Lanka, the Asian Development Bank
and other organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
