<HEADLINE> Hendry Wins Thailand Masters Snooker Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Six-time world snooker champion
Stephen Hendry won the Beer Chang Thailand masters tournament
Sunday night by defeating 1991 world champion John Parrott 9-6.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time Hendry had won a ranking title in
Thailand in nine years and, more importantly for him, also his
first championship of the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
He pocketed the first prize of 50,000 pounds (83,000 U.S.
dollars) against Parrott's 26,000 pounds (43,000 dollars) plus
another 3,000 pounds (5,000 dollars) for the highest break, which
was 138 in the seventh frame of the final.
</P>
<P>
In the 17-frame final, Hendry began in devastating style as he
raced into a 5-0 lead. However, Parrott fought back to make the
scores 6-2 at the interval.
</P>
<P>
After the interval, Parrott took the advantages of the mistakes
Hendry made and won four more frames after the 13th frame.
</P>
<P>
Hendry then displayed why he has been the world's number
one for the past eight years by winning the two frames left.
</P>
<P>
Hendry was clearly delighted with his victory, but admitted
that he wasn't at his best against Parrott.
</P>
<P>
He said this win would give him confidence for the forthcoming
British open, one of the two remaining tournaments of the season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
