<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladesh Tea Growers See Bright Prospects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi tea growers have more
to expect this year, with the average tea price in auctions in the
country showing an upward trend and favorable weather conditions
and adequate rain for tea growing.
</P>
<P>
The average tea price in an auction held in Chittagong,
Southeast Bangladesh, on February 17 was 80.12 taka (about 1.74
U.S. dollars) per kilogram against 46 taka (1 dollar) a year
earlier, press reports on Monday quoted brokers as saying.
</P>
<P>
At the previous sale on February 11, the average auction price
rose to a record high of 118.29 taka (2.57 dollars) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
"During the 1990-96 period, the average auction price of tea
fluctuated between 41 taka (0.89 dollars) and 50 taka (1.08
dollars) against the production cost of 50 taka one kilogram," a
tea grower/exporter said.
</P>
<P>
The price shot up in auctions in the country as a result of a
worldwide shortfall in tea production, especially in Kenya, whose
output was 36.5 million kilograms short of target last year, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall in production last year was recorded at about 20
million kilograms in Indonesia, one of the world's major tea
producers, and 2 million kilograms in Bangladesh, which had a
production target of 54 million kilograms, a broker said.
</P>
<P>
World tea production totaled 2.61 billion kilograms in 1996,
but declined to about 2.5 billion kilograms in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The global production shortfall increased demand for Bangladesh
tea abroad. In the first 34 sales in the current season (May
1997-April 1998) up to December 1997, Bangladesh exported 23.4
million kilograms of tea worth 1.8 billion taka (39.1 million
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The country exported 22 million kilograms of tea worth 998.1
million taka (21.7 million dollars) during the same period of the
previous season, according to statistics from the Bangladesh Tea
Board.
</P>
<P>
The South Asian nation sells tea to some 20 countries,
including Afghanistan, Russia, Jordan, Pakistan and Sudan, with
Poland topping the importers list of Bangladesh tea in 1997.
Poland purchased from Bangladesh 5.3 million kilograms of tea
worth 253 million taka (5.5 million dollars) from July to December
last year.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh tea also has a bright future in the country itself
as the domestic market is growing fast, with nearly 50 percent of
the country's 120 million population now taking tea against only
30 percent a few years ago, a tea grower said.
</P>
<P>
"The home consumption will increase further as the
socioeconomic condition of the people is improving," he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, 15.8 million kilograms of tea was consumed within the
country against 13.4 million kilograms during the previous year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Increase Tea Export in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to export a record
35,000 tons of dried tea this year, 12 percent more than 1997, the
Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development announced.
</P>
<P>
In the first two months of this year, Vietnam exported about
5,000 tons, a 53.5 percent increase on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam exported 31,500 tons to the Middle East, Eastern
Europe, Britain, the United States and Japan last year.
</P>
<P>
To encourage tea planting and the processing industry,
Vietnam's tea corporation has raised its price for the purchase of
fresh tea by 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
The corporation will concentrate efforts on fertilization and
intensive farming on the present acreage of 70,000 hectares which
are expected to yield 10 tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile another 5,000 hectares will be planted with a new tea
strain which can yield 15 tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The corporation this year plans to put six new processing
factories into operation and build a number of smaller factories
in tea growing areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
