<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAARC Integrated Program of Action Reviewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- An Independent Expert Group has
completed a major review of the SAARC Integrated Program of Action
(IPA), said a press release issued by the Kathmandu-based SAARC
Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The review was carried out as part of an on-going process
initiated by the member countries of the South Asian Association
for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka -- to identify measures to
significantly enhance the capabilities of the SAARC to address the
common concerns of its member countries on various issues both
through institutional reform as well as rationalization of the
SAARC's work programs including the prioritization of its many
initiatives, said the press release available Monday.
</P>
<P>
The IPA was formally launched in August 1983 along with the
formation of the South Asian Regional Cooperation, the predecessor
of the SAARC formed in December 1985.
</P>
<P>
It forms a key component of the present SAARC arrangement and
focuses on promoting cooperation among member countries in such
areas as agriculture, communications, education, culture and
sports, environment and meteorology, health, population and child
welfare, prevention of drug trafficking and drug abuse, rural
development, science and technology, tourism, transport and women
in development.
</P>
<P>
At their ninth summit held in last May, the leaders of the
SAARC countries stressed the need to make the IPA more effective
through the selection of target-oriented and time-bound activities
within an overall framework of enhanced cooperation among member
countries.
</P>
<P>
In this context, the SAARC secretary-general was authorized by
the governing Council of Ministers to constitute an expert group
to review the IPA.
</P>
<P>
The Independent Expert Group has made important and
far-reaching recommendations to significantly overhaul the IPA
programs and enhance their effectiveness, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
With its final meeting at the SAARC Secretariat on March 9-11,
the expert group had concluded its work, the press release added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Approves Plans of Anti-Economic Crimes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Russia approved plans on cracking
down on the rising number of financial and credit crimes.
</P>
<P>
Ivan Sardak, director of the anti-economic crimes bureau,
said Sunday that it planned to become more involved in the illegal
circulation of negotiable securities, mining and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
He said the number of financial and credit crimes and
corruption in government offices had risen rapidly in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Recorded cases of economic crime amounted to 210,000 in 1997, an
increase of 7.5 percent over 1996.
</P>
<P>
The authorities confiscated 790 kilograms of gold, 928
kilograms of silver, 135 kilograms of platinum and about 13,000
carats of diamonds last year. False and unguaranteed bills worth
about 18 billion U.S. dollars were seized and 2,200 underground
factories producing methylated spirits smashed.
</P>
<P>
On March 4, Russian President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree
authorising the severe crackdown of economic crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
