<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao: Vice-President of People's Republic of China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Hu Jintao, a top official of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), was elected vice-president of the
People's Republic of China today at the First Session of the Ninth
National People's Congress (NPC).
</P>
<P>
He is the youngest among the Standing Committee members of the
Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee, the highest
decision-making body of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Hu, 55, has been taking charge of Party affairs work as a
Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of the CPC
Central Committee. He also serves concurrently as president of the
Party School of the CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992 when he began to serve as a member of the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau of the CPC Central Committee and
member of the secretariat of the CPC Central Committee, Hu Jintao
has won praises from all quarters for his superb theoretical
attainment and his sure and steadfast style of work.
</P>
<P>
When he was elected into the CPC Central Committee 16 years
ago, Hu was only 39, also the youngest of the CPC Central
Committee then.
</P>
<P>
Born in December 1942 in Jixi County, east China's Anhui
Province, Hu studied hydroelectric engineering in Beijing-based
Qinghua University, the country's most prestigious polytechnic,
where he joined the CPC in April 1964.
</P>
<P>
As an outstanding student in his department, Hu had the dream
of becoming an expert on hydropower.
</P>
<P>
After his graduation in July 1965, Hu remained at Qinghua
University as a researcher and political instructor until the
start of the "Cultural Revolution" in 1966. In 1968, he was
assigned to work in Gansu, one of China's least-developed
provinces in the northwest.
</P>
<P>
After doing manual labor for one year in a housing construction
team, he served successively as technician, office secretary and
deputy Party secretary in an engineering bureau under the Ministry
of Water Resources and Electric Power. This signified the beginning
of his career in Party affairs work.
</P>
<P>
In 1974, he was transferred to the Gansu Provincial
Construction Committee and served as its secretary. From 1975 to
1980, he was deputy chief of the committee's designing management
division.
</P>
<P>
For his excellent performance, he was promoted to deputy
director of the committee in 1980, and later became secretary of
the Gansu Provincial Committee of the Chinese Communist Youth
League (CCYL).
</P>
<P>
During the 11th National Congress of the CCYL convened in 1982,
Hu was elected member of the Secretariat of the CCYL Central
Committee and president of the All-China Youth Federation.
</P>
<P>
And, in November 1984, he became the first secretary of the
Secretariat of the Central Committee of the Chinese Communist
Youth League, becoming the top leader of China's largest youth
organization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hu Jintao: Vice-President of People's Republic of China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In 1985, when he was 42, Hu became secretary of the CPC Guizhou
Provincial Committee, again the youngest of his rank across the
country.
</P>
<P>
He visited 86 counties, cities and prefectures in this poor
southwestern province in two subsequent years in Guizhou. He once
said that economic development in poverty-stricken areas requires
the effort of one generation of dedicated people.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1988, Hu became secretary of the CPC Tibet
Autonomous Regional Committee. During his four-year stay there,
despite the harsh natural conditions on the Tibet Plateau, Hu
visited many areas and made extensive contacts with people in
various circles, contributing tremendously to this region's ethnic
unity, stability and economic growth.
</P>
<P>
During the 14th CPC National Congress helded in October 1992,
Hu was elected Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau
of the CPC Central Committee, as well as a member of the CPC
Central Committee's Secretariat. He has served concurrently as
president of the Party School of the CPC Central Committee since
1993.
</P>
<P>
He was also a member of the Standing Committee of the Sixth
National Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference.
</P>
<P>
Being a leader of the Communist Party of China, Hu Jintao has
paid quite a number of visits to foreign countries at the head of
delegations in recent years, enhancing friendly cooperations
between China and other countries.
</P>
<P>
According to his former colleagues, Hu was a very persuasive
person, and was very good at coping with complex situations with
firm principles and flexible tactics.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his basic qualities as a leader, Hu himself once
said that a good leader must have firm belief and lofty pursuit,
do solid work, seek no fame or gain, do away with air of
bureaucracy and share the feeling of the masses of people.
</P>
<P>
A good leader should carry forward democracy and also be
capable of taking resolute actions at critical moments, and must
love life, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hu's experiences with the work related to youth has enabled him
to become aware of the country's younger generation. He once noted
that in the process of the reform, the Chinese youth should not be
imbued with only only a sense of urgency and a sense of mission,
but also a good understanding of the reform's arduous and complex
nature.
</P>
<P>
"Do not place high expectations while your psychological
capacity for endurance is low," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hu loves literature and art, and plays table tennis well.
</P>
<P>
Hu and his wife, who now works in the Beijing Municipal
Construction Committee, were schoolmates at Qinghua University.
They have a son and a daughter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
