<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Last Year's Haze Costs S'pore 65 Million US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Last year's haze which affected
most countries of the region cost Singapore at least 104 million
Singapore dollars, or 65 million U.S. dollars at current exchange
rate, the national newspaper Straits Times reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a study by a private research environmental group in
Southeast Asia, the report said that the figure is about 20
percent higher than the initial estimate. The initial estimates
had put the loss at 88 million Singapore dollars (55 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
David Glower, director of the group, was quoted as saying that
the tourism industry was the hardest hit, losing about 81.8
million Singapore dollars (51.13 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Health costs came up to 12.5 million Singapore dollars (7.8
million U.S. dollars), and the airline industry lost 9.7 million
Singapore dollars (6.1 million U.S. dollars), Glower said, adding
that this amount was only the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
The study was conducted by the Economy and Environment Program
for Southeast Asia, which was established in 1993 and is funded by
governments and private bodies in Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
Its researchers come from countries in the region, and the
program is administered by the International Development Research
Center in Canada.
</P>
<P>
The study showed that between August and October last year, the
number of tourists arriving in Singapore fell to 1.7 million,
about ten percent less than the expected 1.8 million, while hotel
occupancy rates dropped to about 67 percent in October, compared
with 80 percent for the same month 1996.
</P>
<P>
The study, which was released last Saturday at a Singapore
Environment Council briefing, concluded that while there are no
visual reminders of the haze in Singapore, such as charred forests
and drought, the economic impact on the island was substantial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Reconsider English Teaching in Primary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Education Ministry has
been proposed to review its policy to teach English from primary
school grade 1 since pupils at that age may not learn a second
language well, the Bangkok Post said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Department of Curriculum and Instruction said the policy,
issued in 1996, was not suitable for young pupils who are not
skilled yet in their mother tongue.
</P>
<P>
A research by Chulalongkorn University Faculty of Education
said that pupils should begin to study a second language when they
are able to listen, speak and write their mother language.
</P>
<P>
Forcing young pupils to study another language while they are
not ready will only make them confused and they may end up poorly
in both languages.
</P>
<P>
The department also cited the fact that the country does not
have enough teachers who are specially trained in English
teaching.
</P>
<P>
Pupils are risking learning incorrect English from their
teachers, which can have a bad influence on them for the rest of
their life, the department said.
</P>
<P>
A research by the department showed that English teaching in
primary school grade 1 may arouse the pupils' interest in learning
English but is unlikely to lay a strong foundation for further
study.
</P>
<P>
However, there are different opinions among the Education
Ministry. Some said that the policy has just been implemented and
should be maintained, adding that it is intended to give pupils
sound basics of the English language. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
