<HEADLINE> Singapore Bank Seeks More Deals in Thailand, SE Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The Development Bank of Singapore
(DBS) is planning to acquire more banks and related businesses in
Thailand and Southeast Asia after successfully taking over
Thailand's Danu Bank (TDB), DBS President Ng Kee Choe said here
over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking at potential investment opportunities in the
region and Thailand," The Bangkok Post newspaper quoted Ng as
saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ng was leading a team of senior executives of DBS and
affiliates to meet TDB counterparts in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The Singapore bank's move to take 50.27 percent of stake in
Thai Danu was part of its drive to become a regional player with
global reach, Ng said.
</P>
<P>
DBS is supported by the Singapore government, which takes 40
percent of stake in the bank.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as the first local bank to be successfully
recapitalized, Thai Danu Bank claimed it is in a much better
position than other local banks.
</P>
<P>
TDB President Pornsanong Tuchinda said that DBS has already
injected six billion baht (150 million U.S. dollars) in fresh
capital.
</P>
<P>
The deal marks the first major capital injection by foreign
investors in domestic banks, which have been unable to restructure
to meet international financial standards, particularly a capital
base requirement, without foreign participation.
</P>
<P>
TDB's registered capital was raised from 2.5 billion baht (62.5
million dollars) to 5.5 billion baht (137.5 million dollars),
which boosted its capital adequacy ratio from 11-12 percent to 17
percent.
</P>
<P>
It would now be looking into buying a securities business in
Thailand with the aim of offering a full range of services.
</P>
</TEXT>
