<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia Coming Down Hard on Illegals (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is coming down hard
on the illegals as government officials say they not only pose
economic problems but also threaten the country's security.
</P>
<P>
Illegal immigrants have been plaguing the country which has
more than two million foreign workers with some 800,000 illegals
mostly from Indonesia, posing a headache to the authorities and
causing disquiet among the local communities.
</P>
<P>
What is worse now is that in the recent months, more and more
immigrants from neighboring countries are attempting to enter the
country illegally.
</P>
<P>
According to a police statement issued at the end of February,
3,036 illegal immigrants were arrested during a two-week period.
The number was more than a third of the total nabbed by the
uniformed authorities in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali said the various
operations throughout the country result in the daily detention of
300 to 500 illegal immigrants. The immigration authorities
deported 3,500 illegal immigrants last month and hope to deport
another 6,500 this month, he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi told reporters last week
that a total of 17,576 Indonesian nationals had been detained by
Malaysian authorities since January for entering Malaysia
illegally.
</P>
<P>
The increased landings of illegal immigrants over the first two
months of the year prompted the marine police to deploy 100
vessels on a round-the-clock patrol of the 2,000 kilometer
coastline.
</P>
<P>
Because of its economic problems, Malaysia is no longer in a
position to accommodate foreign workers, the foreign minister said
Sunday after opening the three-day 8th Southeast Asia Forum here.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the police, the Immigration Department, the National
Registration Department and the Attorney-General's Chambers had
their first meeting here on illegal immigrants and discussed
various proposals to deal with the problem of illegal immigrants
including the imposition of whipping for illegal immigrants and
the mastermind behind their illegal entry and intensified patrols
to prevent illegal entry of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Home Minister Ong Ka Ting said the other day Malaysia
had a consistent policy of not allowing illegals into the country,
and the government would not compromise the country's security in
dealing with the illegals.
</P>
<P>
"We have alerted the authorities on the possible entry points
used by the illegals," Ong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Malaysia Coming Down Hard on Illegals (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
To prevent the increasing influx of illegal immigrants from
neighboring countries, Defense Minister Syed Hamid Albar said
three days ago that more Territorial Army personnel would be
deployed alongside regular soldiers to help guard national borders
against the influx of illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Syed said, "The army is ready to increase the frequency of
patrols and extend areas of surveillance as requested by the Home
Ministry."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Army Chief Mohamed Zahidi Zainuddin said the army
was willing to cooperate with the police and the Immigration
Department to flush out illegal immigrants from their hide-outs
since it involved national security.
</P>
<P>
More patrols would be held along the border area between
Sarawak, East Malaysia, and Kalimantan, Indonesia, to prevent the
entry of illegal immigrants, the enforcement authorities said.
</P>
<P>
The enforcement authorities said they would also step up sea
and land patrols along the Thai-Malaysia border, following
Thailand's plan to repatriate some 800,000 illegals from the
country by May 1, to curb their entry into the northern states of
Peninsula Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Home Minister Tajol Rosli Ghazali has warned that stern
action would be taken against policemen and immigration officers
involved in smuggling the illegals into the country.
</P>
<P>
He also said the government would not tolerate employers hiring
more than five illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
To expedite the deportation of illegals, the police have
proposed to set up a special court in the country to deal with
cases of illegal entry of immigrants.
</P>
<P>
Yusof Said, deputy director of the Department of Internal
Security and Public Order at the federal police headquarters
here, said that normal courts take a long time to dispose of cases
involving illegal immigrants because they also have to deal with
other cases.
</P>
<P>
"When cases involving illegal immigrants are delayed, it means
a longer detention for them and further costs for the country.
Therefore with the setting up of a special court, prosecution and
the various process will take a shorter time and they could be
deported faster," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has expressed the hope that countries with their
nationals working illegally abroad will accept them after being
repatriated by the host countries.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Badawi said he would go to Jakarta as soon as
possible to discuss with his Indonesian counterpart the issue of
the influx of illegal Indonesian migrant workers to Malaysia,
which the Indonesian Embassy here considered as a serious problem
now.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian side has pledged to cooperate even more closely
with Malaysia in handling this matter.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia hoped that with operations stepped up at its borders
to check illegal entry and with cooperation from neighboring
countries, the ever-increasing influx of illegals would be curbed.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
