<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Beijing Relay Station Undergoes Restoration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Concerned departments in Beijing
are currently restoring an ancient relay station in Yanqing
County, a northwest suburb county of the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Experts confirm that the station, which covers 162,000 sq.m.,
was built during the Yuan Dynasty (1271-1368). The site includes a
600 meter section of the ancient city wall and a castle.
</P>
<P>
The site has yielded a number of cultural relics, including
over 20 stone stables and 100 stone pillars.
</P>
<P>
The relay station provided ancient couriers with fresh mounts
and an opportunity to rest. Historical documents verify that China
established a series of relay stations over 3,000 years ago, with
a majority of the facilities destroyed during periods of war.
</P>
<P>
A researcher from the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences
discovered the Yanqing station in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Bureau of Cultural Relics has placed the
site under municipal level protection, and the Yanqing county
government will open same as a tourism site.
</P>
<P>
The restoration project is scheduled for completion in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
