<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Liaison Officers Oversee to Textile Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The China National Textile
Council (CNTC) has dispatched a group of over 30 liaison officers
to all provinces, autonomous regions and municipalities directly
under the central government to inspect the ongoing restructuring
of the textile industry.
</P>
<P>
The latest contingent represents the second group of CNTC
liaison officers sent to different parts of the country since last
month's decision to reduce the number of spindles in the nation's
cotton mills.
</P>
<P>
The CNTC president and five vice-presidents led the first group
of liaison officers to six major parts of the country in
mid-February to conduct studies and investigations of the textile
industry.
</P>
<P>
The tasks of the current group include supervising, inspecting,
coordinating and assisting the ongoing effort to reduce the number
of spindles, as well overseeing mergers or bankruptcies of
selected enterprises, the reemployment of laid-off workers and
erasing losses and increasing profits of the textile sector in
various localities. Liaison officers are also responsible for
supervising the destruction of dismentaled spindles.
</P>
<P>
The Central government decided that the reform of state-owned
enterprises should include breakthroughs in restructuring the
textile industry.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai took the lead by destroying a large number of obsolete
spindles in February, with a number of cities following suit by
eliminating over 222,000 spindles.
</P>
<P>
Industry sources note that major textile producers in Shandong
and Zhejiang provinces will begin destroying obsolete and excess
spindles later this week.
</P>
<P>
CNTC Officials stress that attaining the goal of destroying
750,000 spindles by the end of March is well within reach.
</P>
<P>
The textile industry plans to eliminate ten million spindles
and reduce its work force by over 1.2 million workers over the
next three years. In addition, Central government plans call for
the textile industry to turn losses into profits by year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
