<HEADLINE> Sweden provides 3.1 Million Dollars to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Sweden has provided 3.1 million
U.S. dollars to Sri Lanka this year for rehabilitation activities
in the Jaffna Peninsula, The Official Daily News reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The funds described as special humanitarian financial
assistance will be channeled through United Nations agencies such
as UNDP (Development Program of the United Nations) and UNICEF
(Children's Fund of the United Nations) to meet the basic needs of
civilians in the peninsula, the Swedish Embassy here was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
An embassy spokesman told the paper that rehabilitation work in
the North under this program had already commenced to uplift the
living standards of local civilians.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna Peninsula was once the stronghold of the Tamil rebels
who have been fighting for a separate state. Government troops
recaptured the peninsula in May 1996.
</P>
<P>
Two high level Swedish delegations comprising diplomats and
bureaucrats visited Jaffna recently and took stock of the
situation and examined ways and means of helping the local
administration in its reconstruction effort.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman added that Sweden was also keen in joining the
international effort to reconstruct Jaffna Peninsula and upgrade
the Jaffna Teaching Hospital.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish government also signed an agreement with the Sri
Lankan government last week in respect of a 3-year project worth
15 million U.S. dollars for the promotion of peace and economic
development in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
