<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Sector Registers Rapid Growth in Liaoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- The private sector has registered
rapid growth in northeast China's Liaoning province, one of the
country's industrial bases.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the private sector turned out an output value of
58.8 billion yuan (7 billion US dollars), accounting for 16.8
percent of Liaoning's GDP, said Wang Huaiyuan, deputy to the Ninth
National People's Congress and deputy secretary of the provincial
Party committee.
</P>
<P>
The sector now employs more than 2.5 million people, or 7.6
percent of the province's labor force, of which about one million
have been laids off from the state-own industry.
</P>
<P>
Last year, private businesses turned over 2.56 billion yuan in
taxes, making up 6.5 percent of Liaoning's revenues. In some
counties and districts, half of their revenues come from the
private sector, said Wang.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Liaoning has encouraged the growth of the private
sector in recent years to diversify the economic structure in the
process of building a market economy. In the former planned
economy, the public sector played a dominant role in the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
"Development of the private sector will also help absorb the
large number of laids-off from state-owned industry as a result of
the transformation in China's economic system," Wang acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
Private businesses has spread from the service industry, its
traditional realm, to agriculture, forestry, animal husbandry,
fishery, minerals exploitation, manufacturing, house building and
transportation, Wang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
