<HEADLINE> Forest-Based Tourism Popular in South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Nature is calling louder in
south China's Guangdong Province where forest parks have become an
increasingly bigger attraction.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that, in 1997, more than 1.5 million
Chinese and foreigners visited the parks, a 50 percent increase
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Since 1986, when the first forest park opened in this
sub-tropical province, 13 state-class forest parks and 22
provincial ones have been established there, covering a total of
130,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
These parks, some of which are located on islands, have their
own unique characteristics. Tourists are attracted by their
different beauty, including lakes, mountains, seashores, sunshine
and, of course, forests.
</P>
<P>
A local expert attributes the flourishing forest-based tourism
to increased income and the worsening environment in cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
