<HEADLINE> Shanghai Customs Plans to Improve Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Ten firms engaged in processing
trade in the Pudong New Area in Shanghai will link their computers
with Shanghai Customs this year to simplify procedures.
</P>
<P>
It is only one of a series of new measures Customs officials
plan to adopt to improve its services.
</P>
<P>
Customs is also expediting the building of an electronic data
information center to link itself with concerned departments, such
as commodity inspection, foreign exchange administration and tax
departments.
</P>
<P>
As the largest open port in inland China, Shanghai Customs
handled 58.6 billion U.S. dollars worth imports and exports in
1997, accounting for 18 percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
Facing negative impacts of the Southeast Asia financial
turmoil, Customs plans to improve its services to promote foreign
trade.
</P>
<P>
