<HEADLINE> 2,200-Year-Old Bronze Seal Found in Sichuan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have found
a 2,200-year-old bronze seal in this capital of southwest China's
Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The fish-shaped seal was discovered in an ancient ship-coffin
which belonged to a king's family in the Warring States
(475-221 B.C.) period.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, archeologists also unearthed more than 40 historical
relics such as pottery and bridge-shaped coins in the coffin.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists agreed that the relics will provide clues to
the study of the kingdoms in the period. 
