<HEADLINE> Danish Sorensen Wins Fifth Stage in Italy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Rolf Sorensen of Denmark won a photo
finish in the 215-km fifth stage to take the overall lead in the
Tirreno Adriatic cycling race on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
However, his victory was argued by team manager of German Erik
Zabel, who claimed that Sorensen had elbowed his opponent in the
final sprint.
</P>
<P>
The Danish cyclist was only awarded the stage from Torricella
to Sicura after judges resorted to a photo-finish review.
</P>
<P>
Sorensen clocked six hours four minutes and 13 seconds to
complete the longest course first in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
Swiss Rolf Jaermann, second in the overall standings three
seconds behind Sorensen, was edged into third. Zbigniew Spruch of
Poland was fourth in the stage and is third overall, two seconds
further back.
</P>
<P>
Sorensen's victory gives him a slender three-second lead in an
eight-stage race which features 50 riders after the organizers
disqulified 129 last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With 20 kilometres to the finish line, Sorensen and 29 other
riders made their final break. Three members broke away for their
own attack, but were caught in the last 600 meters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
