<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flower Industry Expected to Be New Agricultural Growth Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 16 (Xinhua) -- Experts predict that the flower
industry will become a new area for the country's agricultural
growth, according Shanghai-based Wenhui Daily.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that China has become one of seven countries in
the world with annual flower exports increasing at an average 20
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the acreage of flowers in the country has
expanded from 11,000 hectares in 1984 to the current 75,000
hectares, with the annual output value rising from 600 million
yuan to 4.8 billion yuan. The total export volume is 130 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
For example, in east China's Shandong Province, more than 6,000
hectares are planted in flowers producing more than 600 million
yuan annually.
</P>
<P>
The province has more than 1,100 flower firms and more than 20
flower wholesale markets employing more than 500,000 people. The
province has also established six flower-planting centers for
roses, cyclamen, azalea and honeysuckle.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, demand for flowers in the cities of Guangzhou,
Shanghai and Beijing has increased at 30-to-40 percent annually.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
