<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rios Takes Champions Cup Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Seventh seed Marcelo Rios of
Chile outwitted sixth-seeded Greg Rusedski of Britain to take the
Champions Cup title in Indian Wells, California on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
With the win of 6-3, 6-7 (15-17), 7-6 (7-4) and 6-4 after two
hours and 46 minutes, Rios reached the highest ranking of his
career by climbing to number three in the world.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's a big step in my career. One year ago, I was 20,
now I'm three. That gives you more confidence, you get more energy
to keep on going and try to be better each day," said Rios.
</P>
<P>
The victory was the second of the year for Rios, who also won
at Auckland in January. He reached the final of a Grand Slam for
the first time at the Australian Open in January, but lost to Petr
Korda of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski, who reached his first career Grand Slam final at the
U.S. Open last September, was competing in his third final of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The match resulted in the longest tiebreaker of the year on the
men's tour with 32 points.
</P>
<P>
Despite 21 aces, Rusedski was unable to capitalize on any of
the three break points he had in the match, while Rios broke serve
twice and his steady baseline game dictated the match.
</P>
<P>
This was the third all left-handed final of the year in men's
tennis. The Rios loss to Korda in Australia was another, along
with the Rusedski loss to Goran Ivanisevic at Split.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Connors was the last left-handed player to win this title
in 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
