<HEADLINE> Gustafsson Wins Copenhagen Indoor Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COPENHAGEN, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Second seed Magnus Gustafsson
of Sweden beat unseeded giant-killer David Prinosil of Germany
3-6, 6-1, 6-1 to take the Copenhagen Open title here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Gustafsson, ranked 37th in the world, squandered the first set
but rallied to break his opponent's serve twice in the second set
and twice in the third for his third indoor title in one hour and
24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
This was the 11th tournament win for the 31-year-old veteran
who has won eight outdoors tournaments on slow clay.
</P>
<P>
Gustafsson, who was 10th in the world rankings in 1991, relied
on low, hard shots from the baseline to pin down his Czech-born
opponent.
</P>
<P>
Prinosil, ranked 121st in the world, was 30-0 up in the second
game of the second set but missed an easy backhand volley, which
allowed Gustafsson to come back and break his serve for 2-0.
</P>
<P>
"That point was crucial," Prinosil said, adding the break had
destroyed his winning rhythm.
</P>
<P>
Prinosil, 25, had removed top seed Swede Thomas Johansson and
fourth-seeded Dutchman Jan Siemerink in earlier rounds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
