<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai People Prefer Investing in Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 16 (Xinhua) -- A variety of bonds are taking
the place of bank deposits and stock speculation to become a
consumption fad for Shanghai city dwellers, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Investing in bonds caters to household financial managers who
now have a stronger fiscal awareness, said observers, since it has
a lower stake than buying stocks and higher return of interest in
three or five years in the short run, compared with bank deposit.
</P>
<P>
Construction bonds for 1998, issued by Shanghai Urban
Construction Investment Co. to raise 500 million yuan in funds,
were sold out in less than an hour on the first selling day, in
contrast to 35 days of designated selling duration.
</P>
<P>
Similarly, the 1998 certificate state bonds issued Feb. 20 and
planned for an eight-month-long sales, have been sold for 10.4
billion yuan through banks, accounting for 80 percent of the
issuance.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that the active bond market should be partially
attributed to the low ebb of Shanghai's stock market, which is
undergoing an adjustment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Briton Hickman Reaps Four Wins in World Cup Swimming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHEFFIELD, England, March 15 (Xinhua) -- James Hickman of
Britain became the biggest winner by reaping two more wins in a
World Cup swimming meeting which concluded here on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Briton swam the fourth fastest 100-meter
butterfly following his win in the 200m individual medley on
Sunday, bringing to four golds in his credit after he won the 100m
individual medley and 200m butterfly on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Hickman clocked a British record of one minute 57.98 seconds in
the 200m medley, and won the 100 butterfly in 51.56 seconds, a
time bettered only at the first of the nine rounds of this year's
World Cup meetings in January.
</P>
<P>
Nowsdays, the Briton hoped to break the world marks in the
month as his timings are very close to the world marks in the 100m
and 200m butterfly events.
</P>
<P>
"Being so close to the world records, I'd love to break the two
world records in Paris. But they're not easy. They're tough world
records," Hickman said.
</P>
<P>
He will compete in the last two World Cup events of the season
in Imperia, Italy, on March 25 and 26 and Paris on March 28 and 29.
</P>
<P>
World and Olympic champion Susie O'Neill justified her prowess
in the women's 200 butterfly and Helen Denman, 100 breaststroke
silver medallist at the world championships in January, won the 50
breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Australian Petria Thomas, silver medallist behind O'Neill at
the Perth worlds, was disqualified for a faulty turn in the 200
butterfly heats but finished third in the 50 butterfly behind
Denmark's Mette Jacobsen and Swedens European champion Johanna
Sjoberg.
</P>
<P>
Swedish world short-course champion Patrik Isaksson added
victory in the men's 100 breaststroke to the one he achieved on
Saturday in the 50 breaststroke.
</P>
<P>
Germans Katrin Meissner and Sandra Voelker also savored their
golden doubles. Meissner, who beat Voelker in Saturday's women's
50 freestyle, took the 100 freestyle ahead of Britain's Karen
Pickering while Voelker completed a backstroke double adding
Sunday's 100 to Saturday's 50 victory.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Ian Wilson won the longest race of men's 1,500 meters
in 14:45.65, denying Denmark's Jacob Carstensen a second victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
