(telecommunication company) to the Australian public for 40
billion Australian dollars (27.2 billion U.S. dollars) as the
political and financial centerpiece to a reelection platform that
will be able to offer fully funded tax cuts and increased
government spending.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government's ambitious hopes of selling 40
billion Australian dollars in Telstra shares in one hit hinge on
the demand from small investors and Australia's superannuation
fund managers to support the world's second biggest share
offering.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia risks social upheaval and losing control of its
destiny unless the population grows, Premier of Victoria Jeff
Kennett has warned. He called for an extra 50,000 skilled migrants
in the 1998-99 intake.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's 1,200 listed companies will be forced to reveal
publicly their plans to fix the 2000 computer bug by the end of
the financial year under changes to Australian Stock Exchange
listing rules. 
