<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Leftists React with Restrained Happiness to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- France's leftists reacted with
restrained satisfaction to the results of Sunday's regional
elections, which will allow them to take over 13 of the 20
regional parliaments controlled by the rightwing parties.
</P>
<P>
France has a total of 22 regional parliaments or councils
representing 22 different regions in France proper.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Lionel Jospin said that the result of the
elections confirmed that "the government can go ahead in its
action" undertaken since it came to power nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
Jospin's Socialist-led leftwing coalition came to power in the
early legislative elections held in May and June 1997 at the
expense of the rightwing Rally for the Republic (RPR) and Union
for French Democracy (UDF).
</P>
<P>
The First Secretary of the Socialist Party, Francois Hollande,
said that by leading the right by five points, the left coalition
has uncontestably won the elections.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Communist Party have also expressed with
restrained satisfaction over the election result.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Edouard Balladur and Francois Leotard, who lost
their campaigns for the Paris municipal council and the regional
council of the Provence-Alpes-Cote d'Azur respectively, called for
a reorganization of the rightwing forces.
</P>
<P>
"Above all, we should imagine the organization expressing the
need of unity and coherence... in the Republican and liberal
right," said Balladur.
</P>
<P>
Leotard said that France needs an opposition enriched with more
diversities.
</P>
<P>
Alain Madelin, the president of the rightwing splinter party
Liberal Democratic Party, admitted that the left coalition has
"carried a relative success" and the right opposition "has
registered a defeat."
</P>
<P>
The number two of the far-right National Front (FN), Megret
Bruno, said that the FN has become "the second structural pole of
the political life of France." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Round-Up: French Rightwing Oppositions Suffer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- France's rightwing opposition
parties of Gaullist Rally for the Republic (RPR) and Union for
French Democracy (UDF) Sunday suffered another major setback by
losing many regional parliaments -- including that of Paris -- to
the leftwing coalition.
</P>
<P>
By winning 37 percent of the votes in the elections for 22
regional parliaments or councils across the country, the
Socialist-led leftwing coalition, which controlled only two
regional parliaments since 1986, is expected to take over about
half of the regional parliaments from the rightwing oppositions
and share equal stand with them in some others.
</P>
<P>
What is particularly humiliating for the RPR and UDF is that
the regional parliaments in Paris and the southern Provence-Alpes
Cote d'Azur, which are traditional strongholds of the right, have
fallen to the left.
</P>
<P>
Despite relentless efforts made by former Prime Minister
Edouard Balladur, who was RPR and UDF candidate for Paris
parliament presidency, the Socialist-led left coalition won 40
percent of the votes, against 37.2 percent by the right
oppositions and 17 percent by the National Front (FN).
</P>
<P>
Francois Leotard, the president of UDF, was beaten by both the
Socialist candidate and the FN candidate in the wealthy tourist
region of Provence-Alpes Cote d'Azur, where the Mediterranean
metropolis of Marseille and the major cities of Nice, Toulon and
Cannes are located.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the election results for the 99 cantonal councils of
France showed that the left and right have won almost equal number
of votes, with both of them winning around 43-44 percent of the
votes. Most of their candidates will compete for the second run
on March 22.
</P>
<P>
In the industrial region of Rhone-Alpes, where the big city of
Lyon is located and which has been ruled by UDF and RPR for a long
time, the leftwing parties also scored a narrow win with 37
percent of the votes against 36 percent by the UDF and RPR.
</P>
<P>
Abstention rate in the regional elections, held each six years,
stood as high as 43 percent, according to the Interior Ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
