<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brain Cell Implant Possible to Aid Stroke Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 15 (Xinhua) -- Researchers in Britain and America
have shown that it is possible to transplant brain cells grown in
the laboratory into stoke victims to repair permanently damaged
nerve tissue.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have discovered that human brain cells grown outside
the body can restore some of the functions of the damaged brains
of crippled rats or mice, whose symptoms are similar to that
caused by strokes and head injury.
</P>
<P>
This raises the prospect of helping sufferers of brain diseases
such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's, as well as victims of stroke,
The Sunday Times newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time that artificially cultured brain
cells will be injected into human patients in what will become a
milestone in transplant surgery, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
In their research, scientists have identified immature cells
that can regenerate any part of the brain. Called stem cells, they
have the unique ability to grow into any kind of brain cell.
</P>
<P>
Two independent groups of scientists, one at Britain's
Cambridge University and other at Harvard Medical School in the
United States, have almost simultaneously isolated the stem cells
of human brain tissue.
</P>
<P>
Both are preparing to publish their work this year, The Sunday
Times said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980316.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Left Parties Win Narrow Victory in Paris Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 15 (Xinhua) -- France's Socialist-led leftwing
coalition Sunday won a narrow victory in the election of the Paris
municipal parliament, a traditional stronghold of the Gaullist
Rally for the Republic (RPR) of President Jacques Chirac.
</P>
<P>
The leftwing team, headed by Socialist candidate for presidency
of the Paris parliament (or council), Jean-Paul Huchon, have won
29.8 percent of the voters, against 37.2 percent by the RPR and
UDF team headed by Edouard Balladur, according the estimations by
CSA polling institution, France 3 television and Radio France.
</P>
<P>
The National Front team, headed by Jean-Yves le Gallou, won
17.1 percent of the votes and is expected to play the arbitrator
between the left and the right in the future parliament in Paris.
</P>
<P>
According to the estimations, the leftwing parties will hold 89
seats, the RPR and UDF 81 seats and National Front 42 seats.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Dominique Strauss-Kahn, spokesman of the
leftwing election team in Paris, said that the victory in the
principal region of France is above all symbolic and shows that
the French people support the policy of the Socialist government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
